WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.060 --> 00:00:03.989
It's my pleasure to be the chair for this session, which is

2
00:00:04.040 --> 00:00:07.229
on single-cell multi-omic technologies to understand genotype and

3
00:00:07.240 --> 00:00:10.700
phenotype relationships. And

4
00:00:13.160 --> 00:00:16.920
I'll kick things off with the first talk, and that'll be

5
00:00:16.960 --> 00:00:17.660
followed by

6
00:00:18.880 --> 00:00:20.639
Charles Gewirtz and Andrew Attie.

7
00:00:21.620 --> 00:00:24.800
I don't have any disclosures that are relevant to the stuff that I'm talking about

8
00:00:24.820 --> 00:00:27.310
today, but I just wanted to mention some of the SABs that I serve on,

9
00:00:28.140 --> 00:00:29.600
just to be transparent.

10
00:00:30.880 --> 00:00:34.860
So first I'll talk about some of our efforts to develop single-cell DNA and

11
00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:36.120
RNA sequencing methods

12
00:00:36.940 --> 00:00:40.920
to understand how mutations and copy number alterations lead to phenotypic changes

13
00:00:40.940 --> 00:00:41.640
in cancer cells.

14
00:00:42.540 --> 00:00:46.060
Chuck will be giving the second talk on high-content single-cell multiomics to

15
00:00:46.100 --> 00:00:48.580
resolve molecular determinants of cancer cell phenotypes.

16
00:00:49.780 --> 00:00:53.560
Chuck has been working in the single-cell DNA field for quite a long time on

17
00:00:53.580 --> 00:00:56.870
hematopoietic cancers and has founded a company,

18
00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:00.580
BioScribe, which many people use and collaborate with these days.

19
00:01:01.340 --> 00:01:04.580
And then Andrew's going to give the third talk on advances in single-cell DNA

20
00:01:04.621 --> 00:01:07.100
methylation and multi-omic technologies analysis.

21
00:01:07.780 --> 00:01:11.120
And Andrew's really a pioneer in technology development, especially around

22
00:01:11.160 --> 00:01:14.000
combinatorial indexing methods and studying epigenomics

23
00:01:14.940 --> 00:01:17.820
both in cancer and in normal development and

24
00:01:18.740 --> 00:01:19.780
neurological systems.

25
00:01:20.840 --> 00:01:22.580
So we have a really great lineup of talks today.

26
00:01:22.660 --> 00:01:24.740
I'm excited to hear from all of them.

27
00:01:26.360 --> 00:01:30.020
So just to introduce the topic a little bit, this is a PubMed search I did for

28
00:01:30.060 --> 00:01:33.700
single-cell sequencing papers. It's a field that's just been growing tremendously

29
00:01:33.740 --> 00:01:37.280
over the years. It's a very common practice in research today,

30
00:01:37.820 --> 00:01:41.600
and there's a severely outdated analysis I did of papers in the

31
00:01:41.640 --> 00:01:44.900
field from 2015, but I think they're still about correct

32
00:01:44.920 --> 00:01:48.330
today. The cancer field is still a very large one where these technologies are

33
00:01:48.340 --> 00:01:51.750
being applied a lot, as well as fields like neuroscience, developmental

34
00:01:51.820 --> 00:01:54.110
biology, and other areas like immunology.

35
00:01:56.120 --> 00:01:59.240
So one of the limitations for single-cell

36
00:01:59.320 --> 00:02:03.240
technologies is that although many of them have been commercialized now, we have

37
00:02:03.340 --> 00:02:06.780
great methods to do single-cell DNA sequencing, especially copy number analysis,

38
00:02:06.820 --> 00:02:10.301
but also to look at mutations. We have great methods to do single-cell RNA

39
00:02:10.340 --> 00:02:12.240
sequencing that are scalable, high throughput,

40
00:02:13.200 --> 00:02:15.540
10x genomics, also combinatorial indexing methods.

41
00:02:16.440 --> 00:02:20.100
And many of these have been commercialized now as well, Pars Bio, Scale Bio as

42
00:02:20.140 --> 00:02:20.310
well,

43
00:02:21.360 --> 00:02:25.269
and even great methods to do single-cell epigenomics, DNA methylation, ATAC

44
00:02:25.340 --> 00:02:29.020
sequencing, CUT&amp;Tag methods. Most of these are unimodal.

45
00:02:29.140 --> 00:02:32.580
There's a few now that have been commercialized, like there's a DNA and

46
00:02:32.860 --> 00:02:35.600
ATAC-- Sorry, RNA and ATAC method from 10x Genomics.

47
00:02:36.180 --> 00:02:38.800
But the majority of methods are unimodal, and they do great.

48
00:02:39.840 --> 00:02:43.560
But that's a limitation because a lot of times we do want to understand how these

49
00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:47.540
modalities relate to each other and lead to biological phenomenon.

50
00:02:49.060 --> 00:02:52.720
So I just wanted to brainstorm a little bit about some of the questions we can ask

51
00:02:52.780 --> 00:02:56.200
if we have really great multimodal technologies,

52
00:02:57.220 --> 00:02:59.460
and the biology that we can study with them, especially in cancer.

53
00:03:00.940 --> 00:03:04.140
So one of the first ones is really just understanding the central dogma of biology.

54
00:03:04.880 --> 00:03:08.860
How do things like mutations and copy number changes result in changes in the

55
00:03:08.880 --> 00:03:10.860
transcriptome or the epigenome,

56
00:03:12.020 --> 00:03:15.900
affect protein translation and protein abundance, and then ultimately affect

57
00:03:16.100 --> 00:03:17.160
the phenotype of the cell?

58
00:03:19.120 --> 00:03:23.020
Another one is really to understand the relationship between the genotype

59
00:03:23.060 --> 00:03:26.940
and the phenotype. And so how genetic alterations like mutations and copy number

60
00:03:27.040 --> 00:03:30.860
can lead to changes in the cell's proliferation, properties, the

61
00:03:30.900 --> 00:03:34.100
cancer hallmarks like EMT or invasion, hypoxia migration.

62
00:03:34.820 --> 00:03:38.220
And so really if we can get multiple measurements from the same cell at scale, we

63
00:03:38.240 --> 00:03:39.500
can understand these relationships.

64
00:03:41.340 --> 00:03:45.320
Another important question has to do with cancer evolution, and we

65
00:03:45.360 --> 00:03:49.040
know that we can reconstruct genetic lineages of cancer cells

66
00:03:49.180 --> 00:03:52.340
and understand how different subclones evolve in the tumor over time.

67
00:03:52.360 --> 00:03:55.790
But a real question is whether these phenotypes that we just mentioned in cancer,

68
00:03:55.940 --> 00:03:59.880
are they encoded by the genetics or which ones are plastic?

69
00:04:00.100 --> 00:04:03.920
We know things like EMT, for example, doesn't have a lot of known genetic

70
00:04:03.940 --> 00:04:06.260
mutations or copy number alterations.

71
00:04:06.420 --> 00:04:10.020
And so with this type of data, you can reconstruct lineages, map phenotypes onto

72
00:04:10.040 --> 00:04:12.560
those lineages, and understand about plasticity in cancer.

73
00:04:14.400 --> 00:04:18.320
Another important question is to understand kind of cis and trans impacts of

74
00:04:18.340 --> 00:04:20.880
genetic alterations on things like gene expression.

75
00:04:21.519 --> 00:04:25.080
In other words, when you have a copy number gain or loss or

76
00:04:25.480 --> 00:04:26.160
even a mutation,

77
00:04:27.200 --> 00:04:31.180
how does it impact the genes in those regions, and how does it also

78
00:04:31.200 --> 00:04:35.140
impact genes across the genome? And how

79
00:04:35.180 --> 00:04:38.600
can that affect regulation that affects the phenotype of the cell?

80
00:04:39.420 --> 00:04:43.380
And so by looking at things like subclonal alterations in cancer, you can

81
00:04:43.420 --> 00:04:46.200
start to get and study at some of these relationships.

82
00:04:48.320 --> 00:04:50.820
Another one is understanding cells of origin in cancer.

83
00:04:50.900 --> 00:04:54.760
So in many cancers, we don't actually know what the cell of origin is.

84
00:04:54.820 --> 00:04:58.740
It's usually an epithelial cell, or in sarcomas, it might be another type of

85
00:04:58.780 --> 00:05:02.720
cell. But with these methods, we can link the

86
00:05:02.760 --> 00:05:06.560
programs of the cells directly to their genetic profiles, and that can teach us a

87
00:05:06.580 --> 00:05:07.160
lot about

88
00:05:08.340 --> 00:05:12.150
cells of origin. In breast tissues, we have three different types

89
00:05:12.220 --> 00:05:16.100
of epithelial cells, luminal cells that form the lumen inside, the myepithelial

90
00:05:16.160 --> 00:05:19.940
cells around the outside. And there's big questions about whether these give rise

91
00:05:19.960 --> 00:05:23.040
to ER positive or negative breast cancers, which are the two main subtypes.

92
00:05:24.720 --> 00:05:28.640
And a final question that I think we can address here is are there DNA

93
00:05:28.650 --> 00:05:30.720
alterations in non-cancer cells?

94
00:05:30.820 --> 00:05:31.400
In other words,

95
00:05:32.200 --> 00:05:35.920
can you acquire mutations, copy number events in cells like

96
00:05:35.940 --> 00:05:39.620
stromal cells or immune cells, and can they also help promote a cancer

97
00:05:39.680 --> 00:05:43.100
progression? This is also very understudied in the cancer field.

98
00:05:43.540 --> 00:05:47.270
There was a nice paper by Fuqiao Tang's group not too long ago showing that

99
00:05:47.300 --> 00:05:50.940
fibroblasts in colorectal cancer often have this chromosome 7

100
00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:54.990
amplification across patients. And they suggested that that might contribute to

101
00:05:55.580 --> 00:05:58.680
more of a CAF-like phenotype that promotes cancer progression.

102
00:05:58.900 --> 00:06:02.690
But for most cancers, we really don't know whether these alterations exist or

103
00:06:02.740 --> 00:06:04.380
not and whether they promote cancer

104
00:06:04.440 --> 00:06:08.138
progression.So, some of the first

105
00:06:08.408 --> 00:06:11.978
techniques that were described to look at DNA and RNA in a cell, which I'll talk

106
00:06:12.048 --> 00:06:15.988
about a lot in my presentation today, included things like GNt-seq.

107
00:06:16.028 --> 00:06:19.948
This was by Thierry Voet's group, and DR-seq from Alex van Oudenaarden.

108
00:06:20.888 --> 00:06:24.728
These important studies showed that it's technically feasible to

109
00:06:24.748 --> 00:06:28.208
measure both modalities from a cell, but they were quite difficult to perform.

110
00:06:28.688 --> 00:06:31.538
GNt-seq, you have to physically separate DNA and RNA from a cell before

111
00:06:31.608 --> 00:06:32.348
amplification.

112
00:06:33.168 --> 00:06:36.888
DR-seq, the bar coding is quite difficult. So they are low throughput.

113
00:06:36.898 --> 00:06:40.788
They were expensive and very high costs, but they were pioneering for the

114
00:06:40.828 --> 00:06:43.957
time. This is really around the time that the first single-cell DNA and RNA methods

115
00:06:43.988 --> 00:06:47.668
were being described. There have been another series of

116
00:06:47.708 --> 00:06:49.988
papers, work from Fuchou Tang.

117
00:06:51.048 --> 00:06:53.048
Also more work from Thierry Voet's group.

118
00:06:53.608 --> 00:06:57.388
Also DEFENSEC from Peter Sims' group, and some methods like

119
00:06:57.768 --> 00:07:01.708
GOT from Dan Lundahl's group. And these are all methods that allow you

120
00:07:01.748 --> 00:07:04.908
to look at DNA and RNA simultaneously in cells.

121
00:07:05.248 --> 00:07:08.628
They still have some challenges. For example, DEFENSEC doesn't completely lyse

122
00:07:08.648 --> 00:07:10.948
chromatin, so the complexity of the DNA is low.

123
00:07:11.448 --> 00:07:15.428
GOT is really looking at mutations in transcriptomes, so that's affected a lot

124
00:07:15.468 --> 00:07:19.238
by expression, RNA editing. And these methods are still relatively low

125
00:07:19.308 --> 00:07:22.688
throughput. So there's still a lot of work to be done here, I think, to be able to

126
00:07:22.728 --> 00:07:23.228
scale this up.

127
00:07:25.268 --> 00:07:28.488
And so we really want to be able to scale these co-measurements up,

128
00:07:29.108 --> 00:07:33.047
have better high-quality DNA library complexity that you can look at, better

129
00:07:33.108 --> 00:07:37.068
genomic resolution, and then streamlined protocols that you can perform in the same

130
00:07:37.108 --> 00:07:41.008
reactions or tubes so that they can be adapted for micro droplets or nanowells.

131
00:07:42.528 --> 00:07:45.308
In my own lab, over the years, we've developed a lot of unimodal technologies.

132
00:07:45.368 --> 00:07:48.768
So, starting with some of the early single-cell DNA sequencing methods that use

133
00:07:48.828 --> 00:07:50.008
things like DOP-PCR,

134
00:07:50.928 --> 00:07:54.908
methods that use things like MDA to look at mutations across the genome

135
00:07:54.948 --> 00:07:58.408
at base pair resolution. We've also developed some methods to do single-cell RNA

136
00:07:58.428 --> 00:08:01.968
sequencing. And then more recently, we've been using tagmentation chemistries to

137
00:08:02.008 --> 00:08:05.508
look at single-cell DNA alterations. But they've all been unimodal so far.

138
00:08:07.448 --> 00:08:10.948
More recently, we've tried to really develop multimodal methods,

139
00:08:11.228 --> 00:08:15.168
and so we have a few methods developed now that are in

140
00:08:15.207 --> 00:08:16.688
papers that are published or coming out.

141
00:08:17.487 --> 00:08:20.598
One of them is WELL-DAC that looks at DNA in ATAC.

142
00:08:20.788 --> 00:08:23.808
It does essentially two rounds of tagmentation, one with the chromatin ATAC, one

143
00:08:23.828 --> 00:08:26.307
with it removed. This is now on bioRxiv.

144
00:08:26.748 --> 00:08:28.768
I won't talk about this today, but you're welcome to look at this paper.

145
00:08:29.668 --> 00:08:33.028
Another paper called WELL-DR or WELL DNA and RNA sequencing.

146
00:08:33.068 --> 00:08:36.848
This was published in "Cell," and this is one of the first methods we

147
00:08:37.408 --> 00:08:41.249
published to do the chemistries. It's a DNA first chemistry, so we

148
00:08:41.268 --> 00:08:45.068
do tagmentation of DNA initially, followed by the RNA chemistry.

149
00:08:45.308 --> 00:08:49.168
And today, I'll talk a lot about a new method called ARCH-DR or archival

150
00:08:49.188 --> 00:08:53.028
DNA and RNA sequencing. And this is a new method where we can look at copy number

151
00:08:53.108 --> 00:08:57.057
alterations, mutations, and RNA simultaneously in thousands of cells at the same

152
00:08:57.068 --> 00:08:57.218
time.

153
00:08:58.608 --> 00:09:02.508
So I won't talk about the WELL-DR study too much because it's already published.

154
00:09:02.908 --> 00:09:04.648
It does allow you to scale up things quite a bit.

155
00:09:04.688 --> 00:09:08.548
In nanowells, you can look at thousands of cells, usually about 1,800 to 2,000

156
00:09:08.588 --> 00:09:11.828
cells per experiment. It did have very good genomic DNA

157
00:09:11.888 --> 00:09:15.178
resolution. The RNA quality, I would say, is moderate, and so that's something that

158
00:09:15.178 --> 00:09:16.268
we've been improving on a lot.

159
00:09:17.128 --> 00:09:20.568
But it requires fresh cells, so that's quite a limitation for clinical samples.

160
00:09:21.508 --> 00:09:23.028
It can't really look at mutations.

161
00:09:23.488 --> 00:09:26.668
And yeah, as I mentioned, the RNA quality was kind of moderate.

162
00:09:28.508 --> 00:09:32.408
So, today, I'll be talking about the new method, ARCH-DR, and

163
00:09:32.468 --> 00:09:34.848
how we apply this to study esophageal cancer.

164
00:09:35.688 --> 00:09:39.208
And this is a collaboration and work that was done through Rui Yi, a

165
00:09:39.248 --> 00:09:43.208
postdoc in my laboratory, Kyler Wang, former postdoc, now a PI

166
00:09:43.368 --> 00:09:47.268
in Shanghai, and Steven Lin, who is an oncologist in the

167
00:09:47.308 --> 00:09:48.968
Radiation Oncology Department.

168
00:09:51.388 --> 00:09:55.238
So esophageal cancer or EAC is one of the most

169
00:09:55.268 --> 00:09:58.188
common forms of esophageal cancer, esophageal adenocarcinoma.

170
00:09:59.248 --> 00:10:03.208
The major risk factors are acid reflux that you get, as well as smoking, alcohol

171
00:10:03.348 --> 00:10:07.068
use, and there's about 21,000 new cases per year in the US.

172
00:10:07.518 --> 00:10:11.228
The five-year survival rate is only 20%, so we really need better treatment

173
00:10:11.288 --> 00:10:15.258
modalities here. And, interestingly, it has a much higher incidence in

174
00:10:15.268 --> 00:10:16.808
China, Iran, and Central Asia.

175
00:10:18.248 --> 00:10:21.388
These cancers are interesting from a genomic perspective because they have lots of

176
00:10:21.428 --> 00:10:22.508
extrachromosomal DNA.

177
00:10:23.467 --> 00:10:26.748
We also see more intratumor heterogeneity and aneuploidy in these cancers and many

178
00:10:26.788 --> 00:10:30.598
other types. And there have been some driver genes identified, including things

179
00:10:30.628 --> 00:10:33.917
like CDKN2A, KRAS, ERBB2, TP53,

180
00:10:34.408 --> 00:10:35.748
EGFR, and PIK3CA.

181
00:10:37.708 --> 00:10:40.568
So the questions we're interested in studying here is really what's the cell of

182
00:10:40.628 --> 00:10:42.588
origin for EAC, and

183
00:10:43.388 --> 00:10:46.848
is there switching of cell lineages during cancer and clonal evolution?

184
00:10:48.208 --> 00:10:51.928
Which are the ecDNAs that arise, and how are they inherited through the genetic

185
00:10:51.948 --> 00:10:55.868
lineages? And which driver and copy number and

186
00:10:55.908 --> 00:10:58.108
mutational events lead to gene expression differences?

187
00:10:58.728 --> 00:11:02.508
And finally, are different phenotypes inherited in the genetic lineages, and which

188
00:11:02.528 --> 00:11:03.048
are plastic?

189
00:11:05.348 --> 00:11:08.688
So, some of the technical challenges then is that this extensive intratumor

190
00:11:08.708 --> 00:11:12.228
heterogeneity exists, and so, we need to use single-cell DNA methods.

191
00:11:12.708 --> 00:11:16.568
We want high genomic resolution, so we can detect really focal events that are

192
00:11:16.608 --> 00:11:19.108
ecDNAs that might only be a few hundred kilobases.

193
00:11:20.328 --> 00:11:24.298
We need a co-assay method to look at DNA and RNA, and we want to be able to

194
00:11:24.328 --> 00:11:27.868
link the cellular epithelial lineages and identities to the genotypes.

195
00:11:28.528 --> 00:11:32.508
And we also want to be able to look at frozen and FFPE materials because fresh

196
00:11:32.528 --> 00:11:35.628
materials are not always available and don't have long-term clinical outcome data

197
00:11:35.708 --> 00:11:38.848
available. And we want to look at mutations and copy number events.

198
00:11:41.228 --> 00:11:44.508
So in this method that we've developed, archival DNA and RNA sequencing,

199
00:11:45.248 --> 00:11:49.018
we can look at RNA species, copy number alterations, and

200
00:11:49.048 --> 00:11:51.168
mutations all at the same time in the same cells.

201
00:11:51.908 --> 00:11:55.748
We've done a lot of work to look at QC metrics, and we've shown that things like

202
00:11:55.808 --> 00:11:59.628
overdispersion is very low, similar to our previous methods

203
00:11:59.728 --> 00:12:02.168
and things like DLP from Saurabh Jha's group.

204
00:12:02.928 --> 00:12:06.688
The breadth of coverage is very high, so similar to what we see in our unimodal

205
00:12:06.748 --> 00:12:10.492
methods for single-cell DNA sequencing.And for our RNA-seq, we see very

206
00:12:10.592 --> 00:12:14.332
high gene counts, which is great, higher than what we see for

207
00:12:14.432 --> 00:12:15.332
10x version three,

208
00:12:16.252 --> 00:12:19.912
and much better than our older Well DR chemistry or what we see with Defense EQ.

209
00:12:20.812 --> 00:12:24.642
This is just an example of a human tumor sample where we took the same tissue,

210
00:12:25.112 --> 00:12:28.992
we made a cell suspension, we snap-froze the tissue, and we embedded it in FFPE,

211
00:12:29.452 --> 00:12:31.912
and then we ran the same assay on all three samples.

212
00:12:32.652 --> 00:12:35.912
And at least at the cell type level, you can see that the cell types overlap very

213
00:12:35.952 --> 00:12:39.492
well by the fixation method or preservation method, and

214
00:12:39.992 --> 00:12:43.782
it suggests that we're still getting a really great RNA quality from these tissues,

215
00:12:43.872 --> 00:12:44.452
even despite

216
00:12:45.532 --> 00:12:46.472
fixing them or freezing them.

217
00:12:47.972 --> 00:12:49.692
So in this study, we looked at 12 patients.

218
00:12:50.112 --> 00:12:54.061
We dissociated the fresh tissues, we ran ArcDR, and then

219
00:12:54.392 --> 00:12:57.442
we were able to look at RNA copy number and whole exome mutations at the same

220
00:12:57.472 --> 00:13:01.172
time. We looked at about 34,000 cells in total with these

221
00:13:01.192 --> 00:13:04.932
co-measurements and investigated some of the questions that I mentioned earlier.

222
00:13:06.412 --> 00:13:10.232
Just looking at the RNA data, you can see that we typically see that the patients

223
00:13:10.292 --> 00:13:11.812
have patient-specific clusters.

224
00:13:12.212 --> 00:13:15.652
That's largely due to copy number alterations, which create gene dosage effects

225
00:13:15.712 --> 00:13:19.352
since every patient has kind of a different overall global transcriptome profile.

226
00:13:20.152 --> 00:13:23.872
In the other cell types, we see that they overlap quite a lot between patients, so

227
00:13:23.912 --> 00:13:24.372
that's good.

228
00:13:27.012 --> 00:13:29.602
So first, we wanted to look at the different cell lineages.

229
00:13:29.652 --> 00:13:33.512
And so in esophageal cancer, the three major lineages are

230
00:13:33.552 --> 00:13:37.542
esophageal, there's actually two separate ones, gastric, and then

231
00:13:37.572 --> 00:13:39.432
intestinal, we have three different types.

232
00:13:40.392 --> 00:13:44.372
We leveraged some data from the Human Atlas projects for the GI as a

233
00:13:44.432 --> 00:13:47.602
reference, so we can really distinguish all these different lineages very well.

234
00:13:48.512 --> 00:13:52.272
And then in our own data, we saw that the patients clustered a

235
00:13:52.332 --> 00:13:56.052
lot by the lineages, which were different across different patients, as shown over

236
00:13:56.112 --> 00:13:56.312
here.

237
00:13:57.152 --> 00:14:00.512
And this plot over here shows you that within one patient, there typically isn't a

238
00:14:00.572 --> 00:14:04.452
single lineage. You see one patient will often have multiple lineages that are

239
00:14:04.472 --> 00:14:07.632
present. And I'll show that in a few slides after this as well.

240
00:14:09.692 --> 00:14:12.972
So interestingly, when we look at copy number data from a single patient, this is

241
00:14:13.212 --> 00:14:13.952
one of the patients here,

242
00:14:14.952 --> 00:14:18.692
we can look at all genomic alterations and identify subclones in this heat map.

243
00:14:19.271 --> 00:14:21.832
In this particular patient, we had a separate subclone that was very different,

244
00:14:21.912 --> 00:14:24.552
didn't share any of the copy number alterations and really looked like an

245
00:14:24.612 --> 00:14:28.012
independent lineage. Now, when we looked at the mutations, actually found that

246
00:14:28.032 --> 00:14:31.892
there were a few shared variants, although that lineage down here has a lot of

247
00:14:31.932 --> 00:14:33.272
mutations that are different as well.

248
00:14:33.972 --> 00:14:37.732
And in a subclonal tree, you can see that that divergent lineage or

249
00:14:37.792 --> 00:14:41.532
independent lineage was kind of out here, an outbranch, and it had gastric

250
00:14:42.272 --> 00:14:44.912
epithelial cell type, really looking like a different cell type.

251
00:14:45.512 --> 00:14:48.732
On the other hand, the other subclones were over here, and they have kind of

252
00:14:48.752 --> 00:14:49.752
intermixed lineages,

253
00:14:50.652 --> 00:14:54.371
as indicated in the colors here, some of the intestinal populations over here,

254
00:14:55.292 --> 00:14:57.332
and some of the esophageal populations over here.

255
00:14:57.372 --> 00:15:00.532
But interestingly, when we see this in patients, there are about three or so.

256
00:15:00.572 --> 00:15:03.512
When there's a divergent genetic lineage, it typically has a different cell of

257
00:15:03.572 --> 00:15:07.482
origin as well. But as you can see, most of the subclones have multiple lineages

258
00:15:07.532 --> 00:15:11.332
associated, suggesting that there's pretty high cellular plasticity

259
00:15:11.372 --> 00:15:12.882
here for the epithelial markers.

260
00:15:14.792 --> 00:15:18.632
Next, we looked at extrachromosomal DNA events, and in EAC,

261
00:15:18.872 --> 00:15:22.512
we see quite a lot of these. The easiest thing is if you look at this line plot

262
00:15:22.552 --> 00:15:25.712
down here, you see these very thin lines. These are high copy number events.

263
00:15:26.592 --> 00:15:28.632
Interestingly, in this patient, there were two separate subclones.

264
00:15:28.732 --> 00:15:32.252
One subclone had high EGFR amplification, the other one had high ERBB2

265
00:15:32.312 --> 00:15:35.672
amplification, and that was indicated in the lineages here.

266
00:15:35.952 --> 00:15:38.922
These subclones over here have ERBB2, these have EGFR.

267
00:15:39.472 --> 00:15:42.352
If we look at gene expression, it correlates very well.

268
00:15:42.762 --> 00:15:46.432
The subclones on the top have high ERBB2, and they have low

269
00:15:46.612 --> 00:15:50.412
EGFR. And on the other lineage, they have low ERBB2, high

270
00:15:50.492 --> 00:15:51.032
EGFR.

271
00:15:52.132 --> 00:15:55.752
This is actually important because in the ecDNA field, it's still

272
00:15:55.772 --> 00:15:59.492
unclear how these things are inherited in genetic lineages and whether it kind of

273
00:15:59.532 --> 00:15:59.992
follows

274
00:16:01.572 --> 00:16:03.252
what you would expect for a kind of mitotic

275
00:16:04.072 --> 00:16:07.172
inheritance and segregation, or whether it's just random dispersion.

276
00:16:07.192 --> 00:16:10.852
And so we really see that it does follow the segregation pattern.

277
00:16:10.932 --> 00:16:14.772
We use methods like Amplicon Architect to reconstruct and assemble the

278
00:16:14.812 --> 00:16:18.582
reads across the subclones and show that these are really circular species that

279
00:16:18.612 --> 00:16:21.311
exist at a high copy number level in the cells.

280
00:16:22.472 --> 00:16:26.132
Interestingly, we looked at the gene expression for different ecDNAs and

281
00:16:26.191 --> 00:16:27.751
overall across all the patients.

282
00:16:28.592 --> 00:16:32.452
And we found that for ecDNAs, the gene expression really saturates around 20

283
00:16:32.492 --> 00:16:36.392
copies or so. You kind of see this linear increase with copy number as you go from

284
00:16:36.472 --> 00:16:40.212
zero to 20. But once you approach 20 copies, it's fairly flat.

285
00:16:40.612 --> 00:16:44.382
And so that allows us to understand and interpret that

286
00:16:44.392 --> 00:16:47.812
perhaps cells just can't tolerate really, really high levels of ecDNA or

287
00:16:47.872 --> 00:16:48.312
expression.

288
00:16:50.272 --> 00:16:53.892
We also looked more globally at the correlation of gene expression

289
00:16:54.072 --> 00:16:57.612
and copy number events. And we found that overall, there's about

290
00:16:57.772 --> 00:17:01.532
51% of the genes that when you have a copy number gain or a copy number loss,

291
00:17:01.632 --> 00:17:05.572
follow that pattern. And there's about 50% genes that don't agree with increased

292
00:17:05.613 --> 00:17:08.192
expression or lower expression in copy number regions.

293
00:17:08.792 --> 00:17:11.922
And based on that, we can classify genes into dosage sensitive or dosage

294
00:17:11.992 --> 00:17:15.452
insensitive. And it's interesting to look then at a lot of the EAC driver

295
00:17:15.472 --> 00:17:19.302
genes. Some genes like CDKN2A really has this

296
00:17:19.333 --> 00:17:22.442
linear increase and gene dosage relationship, as well as

297
00:17:22.472 --> 00:17:25.152
KDM6A, another event that's common in EAC.

298
00:17:25.752 --> 00:17:29.052
But other genes, even ones that you in other cancers you know correlate a lot with

299
00:17:29.092 --> 00:17:32.872
expression, in EAC like MYC doesn't seem to correlate with copy number

300
00:17:32.952 --> 00:17:36.032
and increased expression levels. And that's also true for ARID1A.

301
00:17:36.432 --> 00:17:39.492
And so we can classify all the genes based on whether the data is sensitive or

302
00:17:39.532 --> 00:17:40.092
insensitive.

303
00:17:42.072 --> 00:17:43.412
Next, we can also look at mutations.

304
00:17:43.452 --> 00:17:47.242
And so mutations, it's also very interesting to understand the relationship with

305
00:17:47.252 --> 00:17:47.892
gene expression.

306
00:17:48.972 --> 00:17:52.692
Overall, these were the variants that we found and looked at.

307
00:17:52.732 --> 00:17:56.082
We found that about 20% or so correlate with differences that

308
00:17:56.112 --> 00:17:58.092
happen in gene expression.

309
00:17:59.092 --> 00:18:01.282
And so we're showing you some examples here.

310
00:18:01.332 --> 00:18:04.652
So interestingly, if you look at P53, we

311
00:18:04.692 --> 00:18:07.542
compare wild type subclones versus mutant subclones.

312
00:18:07.892 --> 00:18:11.112
The ones with the mutations have much higher gene expression levels.

313
00:18:11.132 --> 00:18:13.732
But if you look at copy number in EAC, actually, there's no

314
00:18:13.752 --> 00:18:17.592
difference.CDKN2A as well, when you find a mutation, there's a

315
00:18:17.632 --> 00:18:19.732
very high difference in gene expression.

316
00:18:20.752 --> 00:18:24.272
And then SMAD4, this is an inactivating loss of function mutation.

317
00:18:24.292 --> 00:18:26.092
And so when you have this one, you see that

318
00:18:27.112 --> 00:18:29.992
actually the expression goes way down, whereas there's no difference in copy

319
00:18:30.012 --> 00:18:33.912
number. So overall, we found that about 20% of somatic mutations actually

320
00:18:33.952 --> 00:18:37.752
had an impact on gene expression, which is different, of course, than what we see

321
00:18:37.772 --> 00:18:38.331
for copy number.

322
00:18:40.552 --> 00:18:44.042
Finally, we looked at these questions around genetic hardwiring and

323
00:18:44.092 --> 00:18:47.452
plasticity in the lineages. And so what we do is we take all the single cell

324
00:18:47.462 --> 00:18:51.282
profiles. We can take a consensus and look at different subclones as shown over

325
00:18:51.292 --> 00:18:54.852
here, and then we can reconstruct a copy number lineage.

326
00:18:54.892 --> 00:18:57.912
This is with a method called MEDIC2, which is based on copy number events.

327
00:18:58.732 --> 00:19:02.632
And it has a bifurcation here into these two major lineages, and then within those,

328
00:19:02.672 --> 00:19:03.912
there's differences in the subclones.

329
00:19:04.402 --> 00:19:08.042
And so we found that some genes like MDM2 are very heritable, so you see them only

330
00:19:08.072 --> 00:19:11.152
express high in one lineage. This is MYC over here.

331
00:19:11.192 --> 00:19:15.152
It's also expressed mostly in one lineage, but other genes like cyclin E1,

332
00:19:15.252 --> 00:19:18.312
you can see that it's expressed across the lineages.

333
00:19:18.372 --> 00:19:21.032
And so we would call this a more plastic type of gene.

334
00:19:22.592 --> 00:19:24.792
So we can do this across all the patients.

335
00:19:24.802 --> 00:19:28.762
So we can look at pathways now and signatures that follow the genetic lineage or

336
00:19:28.792 --> 00:19:32.682
are independent of it. And so we find some pathways

337
00:19:32.752 --> 00:19:36.032
and signatures that seem to be very genetically heritable.

338
00:19:36.372 --> 00:19:39.042
In this case, I'm showing you this example of wound healing, where you can see it's

339
00:19:39.042 --> 00:19:42.442
very constrained to the genetic lineages across multiple patients,

340
00:19:43.392 --> 00:19:45.132
and following here, also this lineage.

341
00:19:45.972 --> 00:19:48.812
And other phenotypes, things like mitoses.

342
00:19:49.152 --> 00:19:52.772
We also saw DNA repair. These look to be much more plastic, and so

343
00:19:53.152 --> 00:19:55.792
you can see that they exist across multiple lineages.

344
00:19:56.772 --> 00:20:00.392
It's high over here as well and here as well across the lineage.

345
00:20:00.832 --> 00:20:04.662
And so, those seem to be much more plastic or maybe more transient

346
00:20:04.732 --> 00:20:08.632
programs that occur within lineages and are not always tied directly to

347
00:20:08.652 --> 00:20:09.352
genetic events.

348
00:20:10.972 --> 00:20:12.912
And then finally, we looked at the non-cancer cells.

349
00:20:13.012 --> 00:20:16.752
And so, in this study, we were looking across all the cell types

350
00:20:16.852 --> 00:20:19.892
that are essentially not the tumor cells or aneuploid cells.

351
00:20:19.932 --> 00:20:23.772
And we found that there are chromosome X losses, and they're very

352
00:20:23.832 --> 00:20:26.912
common, mostly in the T cells. We don't see those in other cell types.

353
00:20:27.392 --> 00:20:30.952
And of course, we looked at this mostly in the female patients, where there's two

354
00:20:30.972 --> 00:20:34.172
intact chromosomes. Interestingly, when you lose the X chromosome, there's really

355
00:20:34.252 --> 00:20:37.652
no difference in expression. That's probably because you're losing that inactivated

356
00:20:37.692 --> 00:20:39.832
allele that's been inactivated by Xist.

357
00:20:40.492 --> 00:20:44.252
In contrast, for the Y chromosome loss, when we see that

358
00:20:44.292 --> 00:20:48.072
male patients lose the Y chromosome, there's a big difference in the

359
00:20:48.112 --> 00:20:51.581
expression of genes. And we can also map both of those

360
00:20:51.612 --> 00:20:54.372
events very granularly to different cell states.

361
00:20:54.652 --> 00:20:58.572
We did this in T cells, and so we see some different distributions across the

362
00:20:58.592 --> 00:21:02.581
T cell populations, but actually Y and X are occurring pretty much across all

363
00:21:02.612 --> 00:21:05.912
of the T cells. And I think the loss of Y chromosome is very interesting.

364
00:21:05.932 --> 00:21:09.712
There's been more attention to this paid recently in the cancer field, showing

365
00:21:09.772 --> 00:21:13.212
that sometimes loss of Y chromosome can affect cancer

366
00:21:13.252 --> 00:21:15.452
progression and also T cells in patients.

367
00:21:17.332 --> 00:21:21.182
So, to summarize this data, we developed a

368
00:21:21.212 --> 00:21:24.792
high-throughput method that's compatible with fresh, frozen, and FFPE materials.

369
00:21:25.632 --> 00:21:27.812
It's pretty scalable. We can look at thousands of cells.

370
00:21:28.932 --> 00:21:32.902
We find that even though EACs have this clonal origin, so at the

371
00:21:32.952 --> 00:21:35.732
genetic level, they really start from just a single cell.

372
00:21:36.192 --> 00:21:39.022
However, they're able to switch, and they're very plastic during progression in

373
00:21:39.092 --> 00:21:42.272
terms of the lineages they represent from the expression level.

374
00:21:43.152 --> 00:21:46.962
ecDNAs are common. They're segregated, usually in genetic lineages.

375
00:21:47.452 --> 00:21:50.882
And we see that they saturate in expression around 20 copies.

376
00:21:51.532 --> 00:21:54.952
And about 51% of the genes are dosage sensitive, so they correlate with gene copy

377
00:21:54.972 --> 00:21:56.672
number, but many genes are also not.

378
00:21:57.512 --> 00:22:01.482
And about 20% of mutations result in expression changes that we can see in

379
00:22:01.512 --> 00:22:02.152
the single cells.

380
00:22:03.262 --> 00:22:06.532
And so the EAC patients have both plastic and genetically inherited genes.

381
00:22:06.692 --> 00:22:10.012
And as we look at more patients, I think this will give us a better understanding

382
00:22:10.152 --> 00:22:13.602
of events that are caused by genetic differences versus non-genetic differences.

383
00:22:15.732 --> 00:22:19.052
And just on my last slide here and to set the stage for the next talks.

384
00:22:20.072 --> 00:22:23.322
Really, I think the ultimate goal here is to be able to measure many modalities

385
00:22:23.332 --> 00:22:27.092
from single cells. Hopefully, in the next five to 10 years, we'll get there.

386
00:22:28.232 --> 00:22:32.212
This is a fast-moving area. So in addition to DNA and RNA,

387
00:22:32.292 --> 00:22:35.852
which I mostly talked about today, we'd like to be able to look at epigenetics,

388
00:22:36.012 --> 00:22:38.672
look at methylation, ATAC, Hi-C conformations,

389
00:22:39.552 --> 00:22:41.552
certainly protein abundance modifications as well.

390
00:22:41.992 --> 00:22:44.652
And I think what's missing a lot too right now is imaging data.

391
00:22:44.752 --> 00:22:48.712
So if we have ways to do high cellular imaging, we can also get morphometrics, look

392
00:22:48.732 --> 00:22:50.252
at subcellular differences as well,

393
00:22:51.292 --> 00:22:53.432
and to be able to do this all modalities at high scale.

394
00:22:53.442 --> 00:22:57.232
And then we can really learn a lot about cancer phenotypes, cancer hallmarks,

395
00:22:57.932 --> 00:23:01.392
how these things ultimately interact together to affect

396
00:23:01.652 --> 00:23:05.632
cancer and cancer progression, and then how we can target that to improve cancer

397
00:23:05.652 --> 00:23:06.552
treatment and diagnosis.

398
00:23:08.792 --> 00:23:10.632
So I think I'll end it there. And

399
00:23:11.592 --> 00:23:13.792
a big thanks to everyone in my lab that did this work.

400
00:23:13.872 --> 00:23:17.752
I especially want to recognize the work from Rui Yi, who

401
00:23:17.792 --> 00:23:21.532
did a lot of the technology development here, Kyler Wang, and our

402
00:23:21.572 --> 00:23:24.792
collaborators in the clinic, especially Stephen Lin for this project.

403
00:23:25.612 --> 00:23:28.212
And I think I have a little bit of time, so I'll take some questions. Thank you.

404
00:23:37.912 --> 00:23:41.172
Thank you for the presentation. John Schatz, University of Miami.

405
00:23:43.272 --> 00:23:46.762
I'm wondering, when you looked at the non-tumor cells, if you did

406
00:23:46.762 --> 00:23:50.032
any analyses of the state of the

407
00:23:51.352 --> 00:23:54.672
microenvironment relative to the tumor

408
00:23:55.512 --> 00:23:57.822
genotype/phenotype relationships that you established?

409
00:23:58.512 --> 00:24:02.472
For example, loss of antigen presentation machinery leading to depletion

410
00:24:02.512 --> 00:24:05.212
of CD8 T cells, that sort of thing.

411
00:24:07.132 --> 00:24:10.832
Yeah. So with this RNA data, we can look at all these cell states in

412
00:24:10.892 --> 00:24:14.112
quite granular detail. And so I was just showing some examples

413
00:24:14.892 --> 00:24:17.412
for the X and Y chromosome losses that occurred.

414
00:24:18.492 --> 00:24:22.484
And-We see a lot of changes at the RNA

415
00:24:22.544 --> 00:24:26.244
level, obviously. So, for fibroblasts, we see a lot of CAFs

416
00:24:26.664 --> 00:24:29.924
in tumor, in endothelial cells, we saw a lot of tumor endothelial cells.

417
00:24:30.364 --> 00:24:34.304
But we don't always see genetic events that are associated with those

418
00:24:34.324 --> 00:24:34.904
phenotypes.

419
00:24:36.104 --> 00:24:39.834
So far, I think, at least the data we have in EAC doesn't show a strong

420
00:24:39.944 --> 00:24:43.894
correlation with those tumor-associated cell states and

421
00:24:43.964 --> 00:24:47.404
genetic events that we have. But it may be cancer type specific.

422
00:24:47.464 --> 00:24:51.344
Certainly, the work Fuchou Tang did in colon cancer showed that a very common

423
00:24:51.564 --> 00:24:53.944
gain on chromosome 7, I believe it was,

424
00:24:55.064 --> 00:24:57.644
leads to CAF states in those cancers.

425
00:24:57.724 --> 00:25:00.744
So I think we have to look at a lot of cancers and try to understand,

426
00:25:01.704 --> 00:25:01.964
and

427
00:25:02.964 --> 00:25:06.104
see if there are genetic events that also drive things over in the stroma or the

428
00:25:06.164 --> 00:25:06.704
immune cells.

429
00:25:07.544 --> 00:25:07.843
Thank you.

430
00:25:09.184 --> 00:25:09.504
Andrew?

431
00:25:10.024 --> 00:25:10.384
Hey, Nick.

432
00:25:11.404 --> 00:25:13.364
The gene dosage work is super cool.

433
00:25:13.764 --> 00:25:17.204
Do you see instances where you have, in some

434
00:25:17.264 --> 00:25:20.934
patients, gene dosage sensitivity and then others where it's not?

435
00:25:21.104 --> 00:25:24.384
So, like a patient-specific, whether that gene is affected by dosage.

436
00:25:25.203 --> 00:25:25.484
Yeah.

437
00:25:26.424 --> 00:25:29.274
So those are really interesting questions, and I think what you're getting at is

438
00:25:29.284 --> 00:25:32.644
differences potentially at the epigenetic layers that might be regulating those

439
00:25:32.664 --> 00:25:32.904
things,

440
00:25:34.364 --> 00:25:35.094
knowing your background.

441
00:25:35.964 --> 00:25:36.184
But,

442
00:25:37.024 --> 00:25:40.544
yes, no, we try to really classify things across

443
00:25:40.644 --> 00:25:43.784
patients. So there was also a lot of patient variability, too.

444
00:25:44.704 --> 00:25:46.024
I think we're missing the extra layer.

445
00:25:46.284 --> 00:25:49.524
It'd be great to look at methylation or ATAC data that could help us

446
00:25:49.584 --> 00:25:50.304
understand

447
00:25:51.164 --> 00:25:54.314
those 50% of transcripts that are not correlated.

448
00:25:54.544 --> 00:25:58.034
When I try to think about things more longitudinally, I imagine that there's a lot

449
00:25:58.064 --> 00:26:01.904
of aneuploidy occurring early on in progression, and so at that time, probably gene

450
00:26:01.944 --> 00:26:04.744
dosage is very highly correlated, I think, with the copy number events.

451
00:26:05.304 --> 00:26:08.664
But cells have to respond. You can't tolerate thousands of genes being

452
00:26:08.704 --> 00:26:12.244
upregulated or downregulated. And so I think that's where the epigenome comes in

453
00:26:12.264 --> 00:26:15.864
and regulates things. And so by the time we see the tumor, which of course is after

454
00:26:15.904 --> 00:26:19.544
millions and millions of cells, I think there's a lot of biology that's already

455
00:26:19.584 --> 00:26:23.544
happened to try to do gene regulation and get these cancer cells into

456
00:26:23.584 --> 00:26:26.284
their high fitness programs that lead to the expansion and everything.

457
00:26:26.384 --> 00:26:28.164
But yeah, thanks for the question.

458
00:26:30.583 --> 00:26:31.164
Thank you.

459
00:26:31.364 --> 00:26:31.624
Over there.

460
00:26:32.644 --> 00:26:36.264
Sandy Markowitz at Case Western. I'm wondering whether you

461
00:26:36.304 --> 00:26:39.964
know in the instances where you're seeing sex chromosome

462
00:26:39.974 --> 00:26:43.704
loss in T cells, is that specific to the T cells in the

463
00:26:43.744 --> 00:26:45.184
tumor, or is it systemic?

464
00:26:46.964 --> 00:26:50.884
That's a great question. We haven't looked a lot at many normal tissues.

465
00:26:51.444 --> 00:26:55.264
We have seen these losses in several cancer types, so I

466
00:26:55.284 --> 00:26:59.153
think we would have to look a bit more at normal tissues and see if

467
00:26:59.184 --> 00:27:00.464
these events are common as well.

468
00:27:01.644 --> 00:27:05.264
Yeah. So whether it's a cancer-specific phenomenon or whether it contributes to

469
00:27:05.284 --> 00:27:06.144
cancer in some way, I think that

470
00:27:06.984 --> 00:27:08.064
would be an interesting question.

471
00:27:09.044 --> 00:27:12.684
Even though you lose the inactivated allele, I think there have been studies

472
00:27:12.744 --> 00:27:16.384
showing that even when it just inactivates one of the X chromosomes, there can

473
00:27:16.424 --> 00:27:19.354
still be gene expression that might be important, and so it's not like it's

474
00:27:19.364 --> 00:27:23.234
completely inactivated. So yes, I think it'd be interesting to look

475
00:27:23.284 --> 00:27:26.304
at normal tissues in more detail with methods like these.

476
00:27:26.364 --> 00:27:29.244
And can you also comment on the state of

477
00:27:29.304 --> 00:27:32.264
technologies for doing single-cell methylation

478
00:27:32.364 --> 00:27:33.304
studies?

479
00:27:33.604 --> 00:27:37.544
Yes. Actually, I think we'll be hearing a lot about that in the next

480
00:27:37.584 --> 00:27:39.424
talk, so I'll save that for Andrew.

481
00:27:39.464 --> 00:27:39.604
But

482
00:27:40.964 --> 00:27:42.844
certainly, there's a lot of work been done in that area.

483
00:27:42.884 --> 00:27:45.034
There's also some commercial platforms now.

484
00:27:45.404 --> 00:27:48.564
ScaleBio, which was recently bought out by TenX Genomics, has a comet tail

485
00:27:48.624 --> 00:27:52.304
indexing-based method. And I think you'll see a lot of new technologies being

486
00:27:52.324 --> 00:27:55.164
developed, especially over the next year or so, that are coming out soon.

487
00:27:56.124 --> 00:27:56.344
Thank you.

488
00:27:57.814 --> 00:28:01.484
Hi. Yashvin Manickam from UCSD Medical Center. Great talk, Dr.

489
00:28:01.544 --> 00:28:05.504
Navin. I was really interested in the slide you showed showing the

490
00:28:05.684 --> 00:28:09.464
differences in pathway variation across cell lineages, and I was

491
00:28:09.504 --> 00:28:13.494
wondering if you could speculate as to the effects of differential

492
00:28:13.604 --> 00:28:17.284
cell proliferation and DNA repair on the distinct

493
00:28:17.324 --> 00:28:19.904
lineages that you see across cell types in the study.

494
00:28:20.644 --> 00:28:24.284
Yeah. To me, those programs make sense to some degree because, of

495
00:28:24.364 --> 00:28:28.324
course, cells, they're going into cell

496
00:28:28.384 --> 00:28:31.804
cycle, but then they're also going out and going into

497
00:28:32.644 --> 00:28:33.824
G1 or G0. And

498
00:28:34.824 --> 00:28:38.024
so it's a transient state. So I'm not surprised

499
00:28:38.064 --> 00:28:41.954
that we see certain subclones that may be proliferating more and

500
00:28:41.984 --> 00:28:44.824
others that are proliferating less, and that we can capture that.

501
00:28:45.084 --> 00:28:48.724
Of course, there are genetic events that are associated with proliferation, like in

502
00:28:48.744 --> 00:28:52.554
breast cancer, cyclin D amplification, RB1 mutations,

503
00:28:52.624 --> 00:28:53.293
those things.

504
00:28:54.184 --> 00:28:56.444
Those occur earlier on, typically, in cancer progression.

505
00:28:56.564 --> 00:28:59.854
So that's not really what we're looking at here in terms of classifying things as

506
00:28:59.864 --> 00:29:03.224
plasticity, because the lineages I show you are branching after the

507
00:29:03.344 --> 00:29:06.684
MRCA. So you can think of it a little bit like the later stages of cancer

508
00:29:06.734 --> 00:29:09.884
progression. But yes, and DNA repair as well.

509
00:29:10.324 --> 00:29:14.084
Again, it's usually something that might be going on and

510
00:29:14.164 --> 00:29:16.764
off and may have higher levels in certain subclones than others.

511
00:29:17.724 --> 00:29:21.644
So, yes. But those are the programs that we see that, at least in

512
00:29:21.724 --> 00:29:25.264
the subclonal data, seems to be a little bit more independent at that time in the

513
00:29:25.344 --> 00:29:27.164
tumor from genetic events.

514
00:29:28.084 --> 00:29:30.124
Yeah, it's very exciting work. And I think that the

515
00:29:31.524 --> 00:29:35.104
slides you were showing with the correlation of specific mutations correlating with

516
00:29:35.164 --> 00:29:39.124
gene expression is very exciting as far as expanding that into the multi-omics

517
00:29:39.134 --> 00:29:42.364
scene, which I'm sure we'll get into in later talks. So yeah, thank you very much.

518
00:29:42.384 --> 00:29:44.724
Great. Thanks. Maybe last question. Thanks.

519
00:29:46.164 --> 00:29:47.764
Hi, Kara Maxwell from University of Pennsylvania.

520
00:29:47.884 --> 00:29:51.644
So I was wondering if in your data, if you've looked to whether or not the ecDNA

521
00:29:51.744 --> 00:29:55.644
load correlates with TP53 mutation status or expression levels yet?

522
00:29:56.744 --> 00:30:00.564
Yeah. Great question. We didn't look in detail at the correlation, I think.

523
00:30:01.184 --> 00:30:04.524
I think that's interesting. A lot of these patients do have P53 mutations.

524
00:30:04.664 --> 00:30:08.024
We do have that data. It might be something that we can go back and look at some

525
00:30:08.034 --> 00:30:09.504
more. So thanks for the suggestion.

526
00:30:11.364 --> 00:30:14.524
All right. Great. Thank you. So, let me introduce our next speaker then.

527
00:30:15.044 --> 00:30:18.544
It's Charles Gewirtz. He's coming from Stanford University.

528
00:30:18.744 --> 00:30:22.164
And his talk is High Content, Single-Cell Multi-omics Can Resolve Molecular

529
00:30:22.244 --> 00:30:24.764
Determinants of Cancer Cell Phenotypes.

530
00:30:28.608 --> 00:30:32.128
Thanks, Nick. So, great first talk to set the stage here,

531
00:30:32.428 --> 00:30:35.447
and I'll continue with a lot of the same kind of themes.

532
00:30:37.248 --> 00:30:41.108
But I do have one disclosure, which is relevant to what I'll be presenting.

533
00:30:42.368 --> 00:30:46.188
So the way I'd like to frame this is the field's split in a couple

534
00:30:46.248 --> 00:30:47.728
different areas right now. So,

535
00:30:48.548 --> 00:30:52.328
as you'll hear from Andrew, he's developed technologies where you can do lots and

536
00:30:52.348 --> 00:30:56.118
lots of cells. But typically, because of sequencing

537
00:30:56.188 --> 00:30:58.828
cost, you have to choose, am I going to do a lot of cells, or am I going to do a

538
00:30:58.868 --> 00:31:02.768
lot of the genome? And so we've focused on doing small numbers

539
00:31:02.848 --> 00:31:05.508
of cells, but trying to get very, very high content

540
00:31:06.248 --> 00:31:10.097
information. I think the field, in general, is moving towards

541
00:31:10.568 --> 00:31:12.348
lots of cells at very high content.

542
00:31:13.248 --> 00:31:16.888
And that's really, I think, going to be driven over the next couple of years by the

543
00:31:16.908 --> 00:31:19.188
significant drop in sequencing costs.

544
00:31:21.288 --> 00:31:24.688
So my strategy, similar to Nick, I think, as well,

545
00:31:25.648 --> 00:31:28.568
has been to really focus on the DNA first.

546
00:31:28.608 --> 00:31:32.208
And so we're trying to make really the highest quality DNA

547
00:31:32.268 --> 00:31:36.088
measurements from a single cell. And then on top of that, continuously

548
00:31:36.188 --> 00:31:40.048
add layers, the transcriptome, epigenome, other things that Nick

549
00:31:40.068 --> 00:31:40.588
mentioned.

550
00:31:41.468 --> 00:31:45.288
And then use that same cell data to try and train models that can connect

551
00:31:45.348 --> 00:31:46.608
genotype to phenotype.

552
00:31:48.028 --> 00:31:49.808
So what do you get from going to single cell?

553
00:31:49.868 --> 00:31:52.068
I get asked this question sometimes.

554
00:31:52.148 --> 00:31:55.908
So there are very sensitive methods for looking in bulk, and you

555
00:31:55.968 --> 00:31:58.468
can detect really rare variants in that.

556
00:31:58.588 --> 00:32:00.408
But you don't know if they occur in the same cell.

557
00:32:00.488 --> 00:32:02.728
You don't know the phylogenetic relationships.

558
00:32:03.888 --> 00:32:07.108
You don't know the associated phenotypes with those, so connecting genotype with

559
00:32:07.128 --> 00:32:10.678
phenotype is not possible. And then when you get down to the single cell, you can

560
00:32:10.708 --> 00:32:14.128
actually do things like compute the number of mutations per cell,

561
00:32:14.908 --> 00:32:18.328
look at signatures per cell, look at early versus late signatures, a

562
00:32:18.388 --> 00:32:19.788
number of different things.

563
00:32:21.308 --> 00:32:25.148
So how have we measured-- What's the most accurate ways of measuring mutations

564
00:32:25.188 --> 00:32:29.128
in single cell? So this is work that's been going on for some time at the

565
00:32:29.168 --> 00:32:33.028
Sanger, looking at normal cells. And they've developed protocols where they

566
00:32:33.148 --> 00:32:37.117
isolate individual cells, they'll expand them over a month or two, and then when

567
00:32:37.128 --> 00:32:39.047
they have enough cells, they'll sequence them,

568
00:32:40.008 --> 00:32:43.788
and with that, be able to get very accurate numbers of

569
00:32:43.948 --> 00:32:47.878
mutation calls. And you can see naive B cells, memory B cells, and they

570
00:32:47.928 --> 00:32:51.328
can look at a person's age, how many mutations they acquire.

571
00:32:52.928 --> 00:32:55.988
So this, I think, was a great review on somatic genomics.

572
00:32:56.068 --> 00:32:59.868
And the thing that really struck me was when you look when they actually quantitate

573
00:32:59.908 --> 00:33:03.788
the number of mutations in normal tissues, in the liver, we have

574
00:33:03.968 --> 00:33:07.028
410 trillion mutations by the time we're 50.

575
00:33:07.768 --> 00:33:11.408
Even in our brain, we've acquired across all our cells about 74 trillion

576
00:33:11.448 --> 00:33:15.328
mutations. And so there's a whole level of genetic diversity that's

577
00:33:15.368 --> 00:33:16.908
hidden there that we don't know about it.

578
00:33:18.188 --> 00:33:19.988
So the issue, though, with

579
00:33:21.068 --> 00:33:24.668
being able to do this type of study is that you're actually

580
00:33:24.708 --> 00:33:26.818
selecting for specific cells that you can grow.

581
00:33:28.258 --> 00:33:30.588
The phenotype can drift over time.

582
00:33:31.268 --> 00:33:35.038
Some cells you can't grow at all. And so it's really quite limited in connecting

583
00:33:35.038 --> 00:33:36.368
genotype to phenotype.

584
00:33:37.788 --> 00:33:41.008
So the more direct way to do it would be to amplify the genome.

585
00:33:41.688 --> 00:33:45.008
But the bottleneck for a long time has been the quality of the data you get back

586
00:33:45.048 --> 00:33:48.968
when you go from one copy of the genome to thousands of copies, you need to make

587
00:33:49.008 --> 00:33:52.948
a sequencing library. And as I'll show you, you typically get these biases where

588
00:33:52.988 --> 00:33:56.008
you get regions of lots of coverage and other regions where you don't cover very

589
00:33:56.048 --> 00:33:59.588
well at all. And so again, the issue's been poor

590
00:34:00.228 --> 00:34:04.208
uniformity or coverage. That leads to changes in your single nucleotide

591
00:34:04.228 --> 00:34:08.069
variant sensitivity. You get false positives introduced depending on which enzymes

592
00:34:08.129 --> 00:34:11.589
you use. And there's really been lack of reproducibility,

593
00:34:12.089 --> 00:34:14.928
which I think has limited the ability to scale to lots of cells.

594
00:34:14.968 --> 00:34:18.728
You really need a very robust, reproducible chemistry to scale to

595
00:34:18.788 --> 00:34:19.948
lots of cells as well.

596
00:34:21.448 --> 00:34:25.428
So what we came up with in my lab, so the traditional workhorse has been this

597
00:34:25.468 --> 00:34:26.609
method called MDA.

598
00:34:27.928 --> 00:34:31.808
Generally, how it works is you have a random primer, you add Phi 29 polymerase,

599
00:34:32.348 --> 00:34:35.988
it runs on for tens of kb, it has strong strand displacement

600
00:34:36.028 --> 00:34:39.669
activity, and then it starts to amplify with branching structures in an

601
00:34:39.748 --> 00:34:43.488
exponential manner. And what that does is it leads to this

602
00:34:43.908 --> 00:34:47.768
high coverage of some regions wherever the primer's bound

603
00:34:47.828 --> 00:34:50.609
first and low coverage of neighboring regions.

604
00:34:51.569 --> 00:34:55.508
With PTA, we wanted to take advantage of the low error rate of

605
00:34:55.548 --> 00:34:59.488
the polymerase and the processivity, the easiness of the protocol, but we

606
00:34:59.508 --> 00:35:02.368
added irreversible terminators to the reaction.

607
00:35:02.848 --> 00:35:05.948
And what that does is limits the processivity, slows the reaction

608
00:35:06.088 --> 00:35:10.068
down, and then we end up displacing those, but we get small

609
00:35:10.128 --> 00:35:13.828
amplicons that in theory would cover the genome in a much more uniform

610
00:35:13.848 --> 00:35:17.788
manner. And so if you look at number of reads or amount of sequencing

611
00:35:17.808 --> 00:35:21.768
and fraction of genome covered, in the initial paper, we compared to all the

612
00:35:21.808 --> 00:35:23.798
other methods that had been out there at the time.

613
00:35:24.268 --> 00:35:27.868
So you can see we're approaching what you would cover in a bulk sample

614
00:35:27.928 --> 00:35:29.528
within a single cell.

615
00:35:30.568 --> 00:35:34.508
And then when you look with MDA, as you walk across chromosome one, this is

616
00:35:34.548 --> 00:35:37.928
the centromere, which isn't covered very well in both methods.

617
00:35:38.328 --> 00:35:41.828
But you see, again, these peaks and valleys, which you'll get a lot of information

618
00:35:41.848 --> 00:35:44.528
from here and very little from the things that are down there.

619
00:35:45.808 --> 00:35:49.088
So with PTA, again, with the same amount of sequencing, same windows,

620
00:35:49.768 --> 00:35:53.568
you can see we're covering the genome in a much more even manner, not as even

621
00:35:53.628 --> 00:35:57.608
as bulk, but much more even, which improves our ability to

622
00:35:57.848 --> 00:36:01.328
detect variants and do things like call copy number alterations.

623
00:36:02.028 --> 00:36:05.768
And so using the bulk samples as the gold standards, we asked what

624
00:36:05.788 --> 00:36:08.868
percent of mutations, germline variants, actually in this case,

625
00:36:09.768 --> 00:36:13.488
in the single cells can we detect that were known to be in the bulk

626
00:36:13.528 --> 00:36:15.168
sample as kind of the gold standard.

627
00:36:15.698 --> 00:36:19.508
And so with PTA, we're detecting about 90% of variants, which is a significant

628
00:36:19.548 --> 00:36:22.048
improvement over other methods.

629
00:36:22.988 --> 00:36:26.948
And then the precision, which this was a few years ago,

630
00:36:27.008 --> 00:36:30.548
things have actually improved significantly, but was kind of on par with

631
00:36:30.668 --> 00:36:34.548
MDA. And so doing things like lowering the temperature and

632
00:36:34.828 --> 00:36:38.008
adding things like deep variant models for variant calling has helped us improve

633
00:36:38.048 --> 00:36:39.448
the precision quite a bit.

634
00:36:40.348 --> 00:36:44.108
One thing to notice is methods that use a lot of PCR, so use a lot

635
00:36:44.188 --> 00:36:48.172
ofthermostable polymerase, which has one to two orders

636
00:36:48.212 --> 00:36:51.392
of magnitude higher error rate, you get lots and lots of false

637
00:36:51.492 --> 00:36:53.872
positives as a result of that.

638
00:36:55.572 --> 00:36:59.352
And so another important variable is looking at the allele frequency of

639
00:36:59.372 --> 00:37:03.272
heterozygous variants. So you want to maintain the two alleles as even as

640
00:37:03.312 --> 00:37:07.092
possible. And in a single cell, they should have an allele frequency around

641
00:37:07.272 --> 00:37:11.172
50%. And this is one of the key features that's really enabled PTA

642
00:37:11.232 --> 00:37:14.792
to be able to call heterozygous variants quite accurately

643
00:37:15.212 --> 00:37:18.412
or variants quite accurately. And so you can see much better than the other

644
00:37:18.472 --> 00:37:22.392
methods, we retain that allele frequency distribution of variants

645
00:37:22.432 --> 00:37:24.852
that were known to be heterozygous in the bulk sample.

646
00:37:25.452 --> 00:37:29.372
Again, compared to the other methods, you can see we don't see

647
00:37:29.432 --> 00:37:29.712
that.

648
00:37:30.692 --> 00:37:34.572
Again, not to belabor the point but the false positives we

649
00:37:34.592 --> 00:37:38.392
see with PCR-based methods are much higher just due to

650
00:37:38.472 --> 00:37:39.952
the copying and the heating.

651
00:37:41.372 --> 00:37:44.972
One other interesting feature of PTA compared to MDA, so Qiagen is

652
00:37:45.072 --> 00:37:48.192
MDA, and in this experiment actually was

653
00:37:48.772 --> 00:37:50.132
Qiagen with terminators.

654
00:37:50.952 --> 00:37:54.752
And just with the terminators, it changed the reaction and the kinetics in such a

655
00:37:54.792 --> 00:37:57.312
way that the small mitochondrial genome

656
00:37:58.232 --> 00:37:59.372
is able to

657
00:38:01.172 --> 00:38:02.892
amplify much more efficiently

658
00:38:04.112 --> 00:38:06.472
in the context of PTA compared to MDA.

659
00:38:06.962 --> 00:38:10.722
And so that's relevant to mitochondrial genomes, but it's also

660
00:38:10.732 --> 00:38:13.862
relevant to ecDNA, and Dan Landau presented some of his work

661
00:38:14.632 --> 00:38:17.632
on ecDNA at the plenary session a couple of nights ago.

662
00:38:18.312 --> 00:38:20.412
Also relevant to things like bacterial genomes.

663
00:38:20.492 --> 00:38:24.332
So we've worked with a group at the Joint Genome Institute and shown we can

664
00:38:24.372 --> 00:38:28.192
amplify and assemble much better single bacterial genomes as well.

665
00:38:29.712 --> 00:38:33.152
So this method's been picked up by many groups now

666
00:38:33.872 --> 00:38:37.812
including Peter Park and Chris Walsh, who've been doing single-cell sequencing of

667
00:38:37.852 --> 00:38:41.732
neurons for some time. And so again, you can

668
00:38:41.772 --> 00:38:45.412
see bulk, you can see MDA going across the genome, the dispersion.

669
00:38:46.272 --> 00:38:50.032
And then you can see PTA, again, not bulk, but much better than

670
00:38:50.112 --> 00:38:50.572
MDA.

671
00:38:51.452 --> 00:38:55.331
They've quantitated this with the MAPD, so the lower

672
00:38:55.412 --> 00:38:59.352
the better. Again, you can see PTA has lower MAPD

673
00:38:59.792 --> 00:39:03.732
with much less variance. And then these are the heterozygous variants, the allele

674
00:39:03.772 --> 00:39:06.792
frequency distribution. Again, you can see PTA much more centered

675
00:39:07.472 --> 00:39:08.672
around 50%.

676
00:39:09.912 --> 00:39:12.612
And so then we wanted to ask, what can we use this for?

677
00:39:12.652 --> 00:39:16.352
And as a pediatric oncologist, typically go back to looking at

678
00:39:16.392 --> 00:39:17.552
childhood leukemias.

679
00:39:18.392 --> 00:39:20.472
So part of this story is that

680
00:39:21.392 --> 00:39:24.352
when people have done bulk sequencing of childhood leukemias, they've kind of

681
00:39:24.372 --> 00:39:27.152
concluded the genome's not very interesting.

682
00:39:27.192 --> 00:39:29.592
It's pretty genetically silent. We only find

683
00:39:30.552 --> 00:39:32.692
hundreds of mutations per genome.

684
00:39:33.732 --> 00:39:36.452
And so there's really not much interesting there.

685
00:39:37.312 --> 00:39:40.972
But what we did is we actually took single cells from leukemia samples.

686
00:39:41.392 --> 00:39:44.832
We sequenced the bulk sample and then took single cells from each of those bulk

687
00:39:44.872 --> 00:39:48.352
samples and then used SCAN2, which is the variant calling

688
00:39:48.412 --> 00:39:51.892
tool that Peter had developed here to get very accurate

689
00:39:51.932 --> 00:39:55.772
mutation numbers per cell. And we found each cell

690
00:39:55.872 --> 00:39:56.652
actually has

691
00:39:57.472 --> 00:40:01.332
2,000 to 4,000 mutations, where there's only less than

692
00:40:01.452 --> 00:40:04.512
1,000 mutations on average detected in the whole bulk sample.

693
00:40:05.112 --> 00:40:09.082
And then you imagine a child when they're diagnosed, they have about 100

694
00:40:09.092 --> 00:40:12.052
billion leukemia cells. So you're missing about

695
00:40:12.712 --> 00:40:16.702
2,000 mutations per cell, but that's

696
00:40:16.732 --> 00:40:20.621
going across billions of cells. And so the genetic diversity there is

697
00:40:20.692 --> 00:40:24.632
just much, much greater than we can detect with bulk sequencing.

698
00:40:25.432 --> 00:40:29.132
We can then do things like look at signatures, whether they're single

699
00:40:29.212 --> 00:40:30.312
cell-based or,

700
00:40:31.352 --> 00:40:35.172
and then, as I'll show in phylogenies, you can also separate those signatures out

701
00:40:35.232 --> 00:40:38.841
over time. In this case, we created three de novo signatures,

702
00:40:38.932 --> 00:40:42.892
one which looks like SBS2 and SBS13 from these

703
00:40:42.932 --> 00:40:46.152
samples, which are APOBEC signatures, which are known to

704
00:40:46.832 --> 00:40:48.272
occur in this type of leukemia.

705
00:40:49.872 --> 00:40:53.792
So the other thing we can start to do is look at different regions of the genome

706
00:40:54.392 --> 00:40:58.232
and what's enriched for. So in this case, what we found was an

707
00:40:58.272 --> 00:41:01.751
enrichment in intronic, exonic, and upstream

708
00:41:01.772 --> 00:41:02.532
mutations

709
00:41:03.972 --> 00:41:07.572
from the single cells. And so this suggests the

710
00:41:07.592 --> 00:41:10.952
enrichment isn't as high for the upstream, but it suggests there are a lot of

711
00:41:10.992 --> 00:41:14.892
mutations in regulatory regions upstream that we're really not looking at

712
00:41:14.932 --> 00:41:18.372
right now that are important. And as I'll come back to, those could

713
00:41:18.412 --> 00:41:22.292
be important when you connect DNA and RNA to be

714
00:41:22.332 --> 00:41:26.192
able to connect a mutation to a change in expression in the

715
00:41:26.252 --> 00:41:27.512
same cell.

716
00:41:29.132 --> 00:41:32.802
And then I've been working with Dan Landau and Tamara as

717
00:41:32.832 --> 00:41:35.112
well on this. They've built some phylogenies.

718
00:41:35.772 --> 00:41:39.092
They used a totally orthogonal method to estimate the number of

719
00:41:39.132 --> 00:41:40.352
mutations per cell.

720
00:41:41.152 --> 00:41:44.712
These are normal cells. It looks like there's some pre-leukemia cells

721
00:41:44.812 --> 00:41:48.772
here. But again, you can see in the 1,000 to 3,000 range, so

722
00:41:48.812 --> 00:41:52.662
quite similar. These were actually different samples, but in the same range of

723
00:41:52.692 --> 00:41:54.112
mutation numbers per cell.

724
00:41:55.512 --> 00:41:58.002
And then we wanted to ask, getting to phenotype,

725
00:41:58.932 --> 00:42:01.012
can we connect genotype to phenotype?

726
00:42:01.032 --> 00:42:03.252
And in this case, phenotype is drug resistance.

727
00:42:03.332 --> 00:42:07.232
So if we take cells, we expose them to chemo in vitro

728
00:42:07.272 --> 00:42:10.252
or in patients. And in this case, what we did was

729
00:42:10.692 --> 00:42:14.422
took samples before and after a month of treatment,

730
00:42:14.922 --> 00:42:18.162
take the surviving clones, and then say which clones became enriched,

731
00:42:19.172 --> 00:42:22.692
and can we learn what was different about them that enabled them to survive the

732
00:42:22.712 --> 00:42:23.492
chemotherapy?

733
00:42:24.862 --> 00:42:28.512
And so, again, for heme malignancies, patients

734
00:42:28.552 --> 00:42:32.352
typically go into remission, but a number of a

735
00:42:32.392 --> 00:42:34.532
significant percentage are MRD positive.

736
00:42:35.352 --> 00:42:39.292
And so what we did was took a sample here, took a sample after

737
00:42:39.352 --> 00:42:40.432
a month of treatment,

738
00:42:41.492 --> 00:42:45.312
and then did whole genome sequencing on those, built phylogenies, and

739
00:42:45.392 --> 00:42:48.432
asked how does the phenotype map onto the phylogeny?

740
00:42:49.152 --> 00:42:52.592
To do this, we did index sorting, so we also recorded six surface

741
00:42:52.652 --> 00:42:56.624
markersSo in each well, we know the expression of six surface

742
00:42:56.684 --> 00:43:00.504
markers. We also have whole genome from them

743
00:43:01.224 --> 00:43:03.394
and can put all of those together.

744
00:43:04.484 --> 00:43:06.744
And so this is just showing you what you're missing in bulk.

745
00:43:06.824 --> 00:43:10.504
So at diagnosis in bulk, there were two different

746
00:43:10.644 --> 00:43:13.384
activating JAK2 mutations in this sample.

747
00:43:13.444 --> 00:43:17.284
At day 29, they were a small percentage of the cells, so we didn't detect

748
00:43:17.364 --> 00:43:21.204
any of those. At diagnosis, there was, looks like a clonal

749
00:43:21.284 --> 00:43:25.264
copy number alteration on chromosome five

750
00:43:25.304 --> 00:43:29.184
or six, and a subclonal chromosome alteration.

751
00:43:29.244 --> 00:43:32.944
And then again, the copy number profile's flat at day 29

752
00:43:33.404 --> 00:43:34.984
because the tumor cells are quite rare.

753
00:43:35.804 --> 00:43:39.644
So when we sorted out the individual tumor cells, in each of

754
00:43:39.704 --> 00:43:43.464
them we found one of the two, almost all of them we found one of the two JAK2

755
00:43:43.484 --> 00:43:47.114
variants. But then we started to see different variants we didn't

756
00:43:47.144 --> 00:43:49.484
detect in the initial bulk sample.

757
00:43:49.964 --> 00:43:52.364
And then we saw a whole range of copy number alterations.

758
00:43:52.404 --> 00:43:56.284
So in each one, we saw this founding event, this loss on

759
00:43:56.304 --> 00:43:57.144
chromosome four.

760
00:43:57.964 --> 00:44:01.424
We saw this other subclonal event that was restricted to this clone,

761
00:44:01.964 --> 00:44:04.104
and then we saw a whole range.

762
00:44:04.944 --> 00:44:08.584
This one was restricted to this clone, was the most common that we didn't

763
00:44:08.624 --> 00:44:12.364
detect in bulk before. But then we saw many different copy number

764
00:44:12.424 --> 00:44:16.164
alterations, mostly deletions, that we didn't see at all in the bulk

765
00:44:16.224 --> 00:44:16.664
sample.

766
00:44:18.004 --> 00:44:21.924
So we then had the ability to think about how do we integrate CNV surface markers,

767
00:44:22.044 --> 00:44:22.764
SNVs,

768
00:44:24.024 --> 00:44:24.374
and

769
00:44:26.204 --> 00:44:29.834
then also, again, map pre- and post-treatment samples

770
00:44:30.364 --> 00:44:34.204
and ask, going down the phylogenetic tree, which clones were

771
00:44:34.244 --> 00:44:36.204
enriched for? So where do you see...

772
00:44:36.344 --> 00:44:39.824
In these two clones in particular, we didn't see

773
00:44:40.484 --> 00:44:44.424
them prior in any cells of those in the pre-treatment sample, but we

774
00:44:44.464 --> 00:44:47.504
see those clones in the post-treatment make up significant percentages.

775
00:44:48.284 --> 00:44:50.904
We didn't see a change in the major copy number changes.

776
00:44:51.704 --> 00:44:55.424
But again, we saw these two clones that really stood out, and we have

777
00:44:56.084 --> 00:44:59.904
coding SNVs here that were associated with those clones that weren't

778
00:44:59.944 --> 00:45:03.303
detected prior that you would think are playing a role, or we would

779
00:45:03.324 --> 00:45:05.644
hypothesize are playing a role in the resistance.

780
00:45:06.984 --> 00:45:10.524
So we did some work with Dan on this as well, and Dan really developed this tool

781
00:45:10.604 --> 00:45:11.284
called PATH,

782
00:45:12.284 --> 00:45:15.834
where, again, this concept that Nick introduced, whether or not something's

783
00:45:15.864 --> 00:45:16.404
heritable

784
00:45:17.464 --> 00:45:20.864
or plastic. So is it randomly distributed on the tree,

785
00:45:21.684 --> 00:45:22.144
or does it

786
00:45:22.984 --> 00:45:26.894
associate with a specific clone, suggesting that genetic determinants within that

787
00:45:26.984 --> 00:45:29.464
part of the tree are driving the phenotype?

788
00:45:30.424 --> 00:45:34.224
And Dan and Josh developed a quantitative framework to really

789
00:45:34.524 --> 00:45:35.984
measure that. And so

790
00:45:36.904 --> 00:45:40.764
as a first case study, we have JAK2 mutation,

791
00:45:40.824 --> 00:45:44.644
which we know is heritable, and then we have a copy number alteration, which we

792
00:45:44.664 --> 00:45:48.464
know is heritable. We have something like sorting time, which we know should

793
00:45:48.504 --> 00:45:49.364
not be heritable.

794
00:45:50.424 --> 00:45:53.864
And we use those as controls, and then we looked at the surface markers we had

795
00:45:54.944 --> 00:45:57.824
and said, "Which ones appear to be most heritable?"

796
00:45:58.884 --> 00:46:02.684
And again, this was a first case. We only had six markers, so kind of limited

797
00:46:03.204 --> 00:46:06.184
in what we could look at. But really the powerful part is the quantitative

798
00:46:06.264 --> 00:46:08.924
framework for being able to do this on larger data sets.

799
00:46:09.704 --> 00:46:12.644
And so the larger data set would be being able to do this with genome and

800
00:46:12.684 --> 00:46:16.644
transcriptome. Again, being able to connect a really high-quality genome

801
00:46:16.684 --> 00:46:20.564
with a high-quality transcriptome and ask the questions

802
00:46:20.604 --> 00:46:23.184
that Nick introduced. How are the two interacting?

803
00:46:23.584 --> 00:46:25.364
How does genotype influence phenotype?

804
00:46:25.564 --> 00:46:29.104
How does the context of the genotype change

805
00:46:29.264 --> 00:46:31.004
the consequences of it?

806
00:46:31.984 --> 00:46:35.804
And so we developed Resolvome, which is a

807
00:46:36.124 --> 00:46:39.704
single-tube reaction where you lyse the

808
00:46:39.764 --> 00:46:43.274
cell. We do a reverse transcription first and

809
00:46:43.484 --> 00:46:46.984
biotinylate it, and then we lyse the nucleus and do PTA,

810
00:46:47.824 --> 00:46:51.564
and then separate the DNA and RNA after the amplification, and then do

811
00:46:51.634 --> 00:46:55.414
paired sequencing. And so we're able to maintain the DNA quality with

812
00:46:55.444 --> 00:46:57.064
that and then get

813
00:46:57.924 --> 00:47:00.584
good quality RNA libraries as well.

814
00:47:01.404 --> 00:47:04.944
So this was the first paper that came out, but a number have come out, several have

815
00:47:04.984 --> 00:47:08.904
come out since then. So Joe Gleason was using this to do lineage tracing

816
00:47:08.944 --> 00:47:09.683
within the brain,

817
00:47:10.484 --> 00:47:14.264
and then look at the phenotypes of the cells in which he was doing lineage

818
00:47:14.304 --> 00:47:14.844
tracing.

819
00:47:16.184 --> 00:47:19.564
So Dan, you can look here in his preprint, but

820
00:47:20.164 --> 00:47:23.244
has taken this to another level. So this is

821
00:47:24.144 --> 00:47:27.284
on normal esophagus, but they've done 3,500 whole

822
00:47:27.364 --> 00:47:31.344
genomes and transcriptomes, and so

823
00:47:31.484 --> 00:47:34.324
built these phylogenetic trees of the normal esophagus.

824
00:47:34.824 --> 00:47:38.704
And on top of that, we're able to find all sorts of oncogenic events that occurred,

825
00:47:39.124 --> 00:47:41.204
could characterize which cell types they were in,

826
00:47:42.364 --> 00:47:46.144
a whole range of things. So you compare that to what you would get with

827
00:47:46.204 --> 00:47:49.394
just a single-cell RNA-seq readout, where you would just get cell identity and

828
00:47:49.444 --> 00:47:51.044
maybe some differences between them.

829
00:47:51.904 --> 00:47:55.004
I think this is a rich data set for mining

830
00:47:55.884 --> 00:47:58.924
deep understanding of the

831
00:47:59.544 --> 00:48:03.504
correlation or the cooperation of the genetics in the cell state.

832
00:48:04.924 --> 00:48:08.864
So then lastly, methylation was brought up, so we've been adding methylation as

833
00:48:08.904 --> 00:48:12.254
the next layer. I don't have a lot of detailed information

834
00:48:12.324 --> 00:48:15.234
to present today, but I'll present to you some

835
00:48:16.804 --> 00:48:19.984
data that looks very promising. So the idea is quite

836
00:48:20.044 --> 00:48:23.564
straightforward. We have PTA, which can amplify the genome.

837
00:48:23.644 --> 00:48:27.324
So what if we could specifically deaminate 5mc?

838
00:48:27.384 --> 00:48:30.864
And so we found some enzymes that really like 5mc and don't

839
00:48:30.904 --> 00:48:34.324
deaminate unmethylated cytosine, so they're marking the

840
00:48:34.364 --> 00:48:38.274
methylated. And so we just treat with this deaminase, and

841
00:48:38.304 --> 00:48:41.644
then we do PTA. And with that, we get the

842
00:48:41.714 --> 00:48:44.564
conversion, and then we also get mutations as well.

843
00:48:45.824 --> 00:48:46.684
And so this is

844
00:48:47.684 --> 00:48:51.584
percent of CpG sites covered. These are different cells, single cells.

845
00:48:52.034 --> 00:48:54.984
So you can see we're covering 90% of CpG sites.

846
00:48:55.784 --> 00:48:59.364
With that, we've been developing deep variant models that can differentiate

847
00:48:59.404 --> 00:49:02.856
methylation from variants using the context.But we

848
00:49:02.976 --> 00:49:06.816
found 80% of CPG islands we

849
00:49:06.876 --> 00:49:10.256
can call, and then we still have 90% of the genome left.

850
00:49:11.216 --> 00:49:12.816
So we can then add

851
00:49:14.556 --> 00:49:18.446
variants on 90% of the genome in addition to that, and then this

852
00:49:18.496 --> 00:49:22.356
is a genome in the bottle cell line, so we have a really good gold standard, and

853
00:49:22.376 --> 00:49:25.676
when we look at the correlation between the single cells and the genome in the

854
00:49:25.716 --> 00:49:26.016
bottle,

855
00:49:26.856 --> 00:49:28.376
you can see very good correlation.

856
00:49:28.456 --> 00:49:32.196
So still early with this, but very promising and

857
00:49:32.456 --> 00:49:32.996
exciting.

858
00:49:34.636 --> 00:49:36.056
In the last minute,

859
00:49:37.276 --> 00:49:40.796
as I mentioned, really excited about scaling to thousands of cells as the

860
00:49:40.836 --> 00:49:44.116
sequencing prices drop. So for example,

861
00:49:44.656 --> 00:49:47.176
Ultima has announced an $80 whole genome.

862
00:49:47.536 --> 00:49:51.456
They do 30X whole genome. Most people using our technology do

863
00:49:51.516 --> 00:49:55.496
a 10X whole genome, so that gets to $26 or $27

864
00:49:55.976 --> 00:49:56.595
per genome.

865
00:49:57.496 --> 00:50:01.316
And so at that rate, you can think about doing thousands of cells,

866
00:50:02.096 --> 00:50:05.796
and really getting deep information if we had genome

867
00:50:07.096 --> 00:50:11.056
transcriptome, and then we think we can do genome transcriptome and methylation

868
00:50:11.216 --> 00:50:15.096
in the same cell as well. But number of other sequencing offerings,

869
00:50:15.136 --> 00:50:18.856
so it will be interesting to see how we can really scale

870
00:50:19.356 --> 00:50:22.716
as that limiting factor gets dealt with.

871
00:50:23.756 --> 00:50:27.436
And so again, getting back to AI, I think just a couple take-home

872
00:50:27.496 --> 00:50:31.316
points real quickly. So I think there have been a lot of things on

873
00:50:31.336 --> 00:50:34.696
virtual cells, just looking at low content data,

874
00:50:35.176 --> 00:50:39.076
perturb-seq studies in cell lines, and I think to

875
00:50:39.116 --> 00:50:43.036
get really deep models of tissue, we need really deep

876
00:50:43.076 --> 00:50:45.316
information and we need primary samples.

877
00:50:45.376 --> 00:50:48.636
And so that's what we're working towards.

878
00:50:49.556 --> 00:50:53.176
And again, the rare cells is what we care about, which are lost in

879
00:50:53.276 --> 00:50:56.966
bulk. And so if you have a treatment-resistant cell, you can build

880
00:50:57.436 --> 00:51:01.036
a phylogenetic tree, you can understand the context of it, you can layer on

881
00:51:01.056 --> 00:51:04.916
phenotypic information. But ultimately, I think that

882
00:51:04.956 --> 00:51:08.836
deep information is what's going to lead to biomarkers that are directed towards

883
00:51:09.256 --> 00:51:11.536
the cells you really want to kill or

884
00:51:12.476 --> 00:51:15.585
to-- because they're the cells that are actually going to determine the outcome of

885
00:51:15.616 --> 00:51:16.216
the patient.

886
00:51:17.056 --> 00:51:20.736
And so with that, I thank the organizing committee

887
00:51:20.796 --> 00:51:23.836
again for the invitation and happy to answer questions.

888
00:51:46.836 --> 00:51:48.616
Hey, Chuck. A really nice talk.

889
00:51:49.596 --> 00:51:52.756
I was wondering if you could tell us a little bit more just about the

890
00:51:53.556 --> 00:51:56.376
scaling things up. What are the challenges?

891
00:51:56.496 --> 00:52:00.336
Are there any strategies you're thinking

892
00:52:00.436 --> 00:52:01.336
about?

893
00:52:01.556 --> 00:52:01.696
Yeah.

894
00:52:01.896 --> 00:52:05.756
Because you have really wonderful data sets, very high quality, very deep

895
00:52:05.816 --> 00:52:06.096
data.

896
00:52:07.036 --> 00:52:09.066
But it'd be nice to scale things up if there's-

897
00:52:09.176 --> 00:52:12.696
Yeah, no. It's something I've thought quite a bit about.

898
00:52:14.356 --> 00:52:17.176
Typically, droplet-based approaches are

899
00:52:17.816 --> 00:52:20.596
problematic for us because we have multi-step chemistry.

900
00:52:21.276 --> 00:52:24.746
And so most droplet approaches are one or two steps, whether it's

901
00:52:25.276 --> 00:52:28.816
10X or Mission Bio. And so those aren't really compatible.

902
00:52:28.916 --> 00:52:32.516
The other thing is we like to have bigger volumes.

903
00:52:33.616 --> 00:52:37.576
So having teeny, teeny volumes is, I think, problematic when you're trying

904
00:52:37.616 --> 00:52:38.835
to amplify a whole genome.

905
00:52:39.716 --> 00:52:43.496
And so the first step we've done is

906
00:52:43.516 --> 00:52:46.716
really to make the chemistry so it's completely additive.

907
00:52:47.576 --> 00:52:49.976
So you can't have cleanups as you go to high throughput.

908
00:52:50.036 --> 00:52:53.676
So being able to have the chemistry tolerate a barcode within the chemistry,

909
00:52:54.496 --> 00:52:57.056
which we've been successfully able to do.

910
00:52:57.836 --> 00:53:01.596
There are other methods out there with combinatorial indexing is a powerful tool

911
00:53:01.696 --> 00:53:05.676
for trying to do that. We've been thinking about ways to do that

912
00:53:05.776 --> 00:53:06.936
but haven't come up with

913
00:53:07.936 --> 00:53:11.856
a real solution. But I think the first thing is getting the chemistry so

914
00:53:11.896 --> 00:53:15.536
it's deployable within a completely additive environment.

915
00:53:16.056 --> 00:53:19.536
And then scaling. The plan we have right now

916
00:53:20.275 --> 00:53:23.976
is working with HP. They have a--

917
00:53:24.176 --> 00:53:27.836
or Tikan, they have a liquid dispenser that's based on

918
00:53:27.896 --> 00:53:31.376
inkjet printing, and it can do teeny, teeny volumes, and it can

919
00:53:31.416 --> 00:53:35.366
do 1536 plate. There are other challenges with that,

920
00:53:35.456 --> 00:53:36.676
but I think we may have solved that.

921
00:53:36.696 --> 00:53:39.436
But I think we'll be able to get to 1536 pretty quick.

922
00:53:40.076 --> 00:53:43.696
But being able to scale to tens of thousands of cells is going to

923
00:53:43.756 --> 00:53:45.116
take a little time.

924
00:53:46.536 --> 00:53:50.436
But again, the sequencing cost. To me, if you look at doing

925
00:53:50.476 --> 00:53:54.446
an exome capture, you want to do a methylome and exome capture, it almost

926
00:53:54.476 --> 00:53:58.116
becomes cheaper at this point to do whole-genome sequencing.

927
00:53:58.136 --> 00:53:58.876
And so

928
00:53:59.916 --> 00:54:03.036
I think pushing-- And as the sequencing keeps coming

929
00:54:03.096 --> 00:54:06.876
down, we can continue to ramp up the number of cells we look at.

930
00:54:11.356 --> 00:54:11.426
Thanks.

931
00:54:11.426 --> 00:54:11.636
Thanks.

932
00:54:21.436 --> 00:54:25.236
And our next speaker is Andrew Addy from OHSU, and he'll be talking

933
00:54:25.276 --> 00:54:28.116
about single-cell DNA methylation multi-omic technologies.

934
00:54:30.276 --> 00:54:31.136
All right. Thanks.

935
00:54:32.636 --> 00:54:34.656
Yeah. So, first, thanks for the invitation.

936
00:54:34.696 --> 00:54:37.736
I'm excited to be here, especially in a technology session.

937
00:54:38.056 --> 00:54:41.116
I get to talk about one of my core passions, which is technology development.

938
00:54:41.156 --> 00:54:42.876
So it's going to be technology-heavy.

939
00:54:43.836 --> 00:54:47.516
And talking about what motivated us to develop these technologies,

940
00:54:48.276 --> 00:54:51.436
how we've gotten to where we're at now, and really what our current capabilities

941
00:54:51.536 --> 00:54:53.526
are to look at DNA methylation and multi-omics.

942
00:54:54.236 --> 00:54:56.326
Some disclosures which are relevant to

943
00:54:57.776 --> 00:54:58.326
my talk today.

944
00:54:59.676 --> 00:55:02.716
So first, DNA methylation, this is the property that I've really been pursuing the

945
00:55:02.756 --> 00:55:03.596
most throughout my career.

946
00:55:04.896 --> 00:55:06.676
And what's the motivation for that?

947
00:55:06.756 --> 00:55:10.748
AndMany of you are aware, this is review, but

948
00:55:10.828 --> 00:55:14.528
in mammalian genomes, DNA methylation is typically this

949
00:55:14.628 --> 00:55:18.228
methyl group on the five carbon of cytosine bases in this CG or

950
00:55:18.318 --> 00:55:19.448
CpG context.

951
00:55:20.768 --> 00:55:24.468
We often represent it as kind of like these lollipops, and the CG

952
00:55:24.508 --> 00:55:28.478
dinucleotide context is the rarest in the genome because it has this regulatory

953
00:55:28.478 --> 00:55:28.648
role.

954
00:55:30.008 --> 00:55:33.928
And typically 60% to 80% of these CG sites are methylated genome-wide in

955
00:55:33.968 --> 00:55:35.328
a typical mammalian cell type.

956
00:55:36.308 --> 00:55:38.388
Whereas the non-CG sites are

957
00:55:39.528 --> 00:55:41.408
typically completely non-methylated.

958
00:55:42.908 --> 00:55:44.908
There are some exceptions that I'll touch on a little bit later.

959
00:55:47.088 --> 00:55:50.048
So generally, DNA methylation is associated with repression.

960
00:55:51.488 --> 00:55:55.208
I like to think of it as this initial gatekeeper of genomic permissiveness,

961
00:55:55.688 --> 00:55:59.648
where the DNA methylation patterns really dictate which regions

962
00:55:59.658 --> 00:56:02.258
of the genome have the potential for activation.

963
00:56:02.848 --> 00:56:06.548
So often, DNA methylation of a promoter isn't going to correlate well with

964
00:56:06.588 --> 00:56:10.398
expression. It's a common kind of misconception and an over-assumption.

965
00:56:10.828 --> 00:56:14.208
It really correlates with the capability of a gene to become

966
00:56:14.288 --> 00:56:18.238
activated, that the next layers of epigenetic machinery, such as open chromatin,

967
00:56:18.808 --> 00:56:22.588
actuating that open chromatin with a transcription factor to then lead to

968
00:56:23.208 --> 00:56:26.128
active transcription. And because it forms this

969
00:56:27.168 --> 00:56:31.028
real masking role of the genome, it really makes it the most basal layer

970
00:56:31.088 --> 00:56:32.848
of epigenomic regulatory control.

971
00:56:32.928 --> 00:56:36.518
So it's kind of that first layer of gene regulation when you're looking at the

972
00:56:36.548 --> 00:56:39.008
whole spectrum of gene regulatory dynamics.

973
00:56:40.788 --> 00:56:44.488
We know a lot about some of the nitty-gritty mechanisms of

974
00:56:44.668 --> 00:56:48.228
how it works. DNMT1, for example, is the methylation

975
00:56:48.688 --> 00:56:49.868
transferase that does maintenance.

976
00:56:49.928 --> 00:56:53.848
So when you have a new cell division, it copies over the methyl groups at these CG

977
00:56:53.888 --> 00:56:57.108
sites. And then we know Tet proteins can

978
00:56:57.168 --> 00:57:00.288
target loci for removal of DNA methylation.

979
00:57:00.668 --> 00:57:04.428
And then de novo deposition of methylation is with DNMT3A or 3B.

980
00:57:05.348 --> 00:57:08.518
And many of you will recognize these genes if you study any

981
00:57:09.508 --> 00:57:10.948
blood cancers,

982
00:57:12.168 --> 00:57:16.088
whereas Tet2 and DNMT3A are two of the major top driver genes in

983
00:57:16.148 --> 00:57:16.468
AML.

984
00:57:18.588 --> 00:57:22.308
Which then brings us to the role of DNA methylation in development and

985
00:57:22.328 --> 00:57:26.058
disease, where cancer genomes-- And

986
00:57:26.308 --> 00:57:29.528
I have the title of this slide is "DNA methylation is almost always altered in

987
00:57:29.568 --> 00:57:33.328
cancer." I have yet to find a paper that's really studied DNA

988
00:57:33.368 --> 00:57:36.888
methylation in cancer and has not found significant alterations.

989
00:57:37.408 --> 00:57:40.688
And pretty frequently across a broad spectrum of cancers, you get this

990
00:57:40.708 --> 00:57:44.488
hypomethylation phenotype, where large swaths of the genome end up being

991
00:57:44.528 --> 00:57:47.028
hypomethylated and a reduction in that methylated level.

992
00:57:48.028 --> 00:57:51.448
This can lead to things like retrotransposable element activation, which can then

993
00:57:51.488 --> 00:57:52.548
lead to genome instability,

994
00:57:53.888 --> 00:57:57.858
or hypomethylation of promoters that can lead to activation

995
00:57:57.888 --> 00:58:01.868
of oncogenes. And more broadly, this really makes a lot of

996
00:58:01.928 --> 00:58:05.608
sense with cancer because you get global hypomethylation, which then leads to this

997
00:58:05.728 --> 00:58:09.628
reduction of that filter of regulatory control and repression on the

998
00:58:09.648 --> 00:58:13.368
genome that gives a lot more pathways that are available for activation.

999
00:58:13.888 --> 00:58:17.748
Cancer cells want to adapt and evolve, and removal of that

1000
00:58:17.768 --> 00:58:21.558
methylation kind of frees things up to enable them to explore those other

1001
00:58:21.608 --> 00:58:25.568
pathways and increase the cell state plasticity and ability to

1002
00:58:25.628 --> 00:58:27.678
adapt to external extrinsic pressures.

1003
00:58:29.088 --> 00:58:31.028
It's also a massive signal for cell-free DNA.

1004
00:58:31.688 --> 00:58:35.378
If you've looked at a lot of the work from GRAIL, for example, you see a lot of

1005
00:58:35.688 --> 00:58:39.508
cell-free DNA methylation that's being used for diagnostic purposes.

1006
00:58:40.848 --> 00:58:44.528
So like other properties, this is cell type specific, so it really

1007
00:58:44.548 --> 00:58:46.668
requires single-cell resolution to enable

1008
00:58:47.628 --> 00:58:49.388
looking at it and understanding this property.

1009
00:58:49.408 --> 00:58:53.328
But it's been traditionally much more difficult to look at methylation than

1010
00:58:53.368 --> 00:58:54.408
some of these other properties.

1011
00:58:55.908 --> 00:58:57.888
A lot of this comes down to the conversion approach.

1012
00:58:58.228 --> 00:59:02.108
So like what Chuck was saying, there's multiple steps that are required

1013
00:59:02.168 --> 00:59:05.788
to do this conversion, whether you're doing the traditional method where you

1014
00:59:05.828 --> 00:59:09.128
convert all cytosines to uracil and then methylated cytosines retain

1015
00:59:09.148 --> 00:59:10.948
their cytosine identity,

1016
00:59:11.808 --> 00:59:13.858
or flipping it with some of these newer chemistries

1017
00:59:14.668 --> 00:59:17.568
with methylcytosine-specific deaminases.

1018
00:59:18.688 --> 00:59:22.538
It still requires multiple steps, harsh chemicals, and it makes it

1019
00:59:22.608 --> 00:59:26.147
trickier to enable high-throughput single-cell technologies.

1020
00:59:27.388 --> 00:59:31.268
As a result, most techniques previously have been developed where it's single

1021
00:59:31.348 --> 00:59:32.108
cell, single well.

1022
00:59:33.428 --> 00:59:36.638
And some of these can produce great quality data, but it is inherently lower

1023
00:59:36.708 --> 00:59:40.028
throughput. And there's a place for low throughput, high coverage, as Chuck was

1024
00:59:40.068 --> 00:59:42.508
just showing. We're shifting things in a different direction.

1025
00:59:42.548 --> 00:59:45.748
We tend to do a little lower coverage, but much higher throughput, and it's just

1026
00:59:45.788 --> 00:59:47.088
not amenable with these approaches.

1027
00:59:47.228 --> 00:59:47.868
Though,

1028
00:59:48.848 --> 00:59:52.748
there is an exception. This method, SNm-C-seq from Joe Ecker,

1029
00:59:52.768 --> 00:59:56.428
who's at San Diego at the Salk Institute, who's really a pioneer in the

1030
00:59:56.468 --> 00:59:57.268
methylation space.

1031
00:59:58.328 --> 00:59:59.948
They just brute forced it with automation.

1032
01:00:00.608 --> 01:00:04.028
And here's an example from one of their studies from the BRAIN Initiative.

1033
01:00:04.068 --> 01:00:07.668
Over half a million cells that are really high coverage, high-quality

1034
01:00:07.708 --> 01:00:11.008
methylomes. But when you look at what it took to generate this data set,

1035
01:00:12.588 --> 01:00:16.368
it's almost 5,400 384 well plates with a large

1036
01:00:16.408 --> 01:00:18.868
portion of those actually 384 well column cleanups.

1037
01:00:19.488 --> 01:00:23.168
So just in plasticware alone, that's pretty inhibiting for most groups.

1038
01:00:23.508 --> 01:00:25.108
And I'm not saying this to take away from the paper.

1039
01:00:25.188 --> 01:00:28.678
I want to emphasize just the amount of work that went into producing this beautiful

1040
01:00:28.678 --> 01:00:29.068
atlas.

1041
01:00:30.048 --> 01:00:33.368
But I can't do that. Most labs don't have the storage space for that much

1042
01:00:33.388 --> 01:00:37.348
plasticware. So that's motivated us

1043
01:00:37.408 --> 01:00:39.088
to develop our technology, SKY-Met.

1044
01:00:40.528 --> 01:00:42.468
And this is a combinatorial indexing approach.

1045
01:00:42.708 --> 01:00:46.048
So we do two tiers of cell barcoding, the first being

1046
01:00:46.168 --> 01:00:48.008
tagmentation using indexed adapters.

1047
01:00:48.708 --> 01:00:52.528
We then pool these intact nuclei together, split them out, and then append a

1048
01:00:52.588 --> 01:00:55.168
second barcode. So this is the multi-tier barcoding.

1049
01:00:55.228 --> 01:00:57.657
So you can see in the kind of bottom well of this

1050
01:00:58.648 --> 01:01:02.018
examples here. There's multiple cells in the well, but they each have

1051
01:01:02.128 --> 01:01:05.868
unique barcode combinations, and it's that combination that gives us our unique

1052
01:01:05.908 --> 01:01:06.268
index.

1053
01:01:07.768 --> 01:01:11.628
So for methylation, though, if we wanted to do this where we do

1054
01:01:11.688 --> 01:01:15.598
in situ tagmentation, the first challenge is that this is the first

1055
01:01:15.688 --> 01:01:19.040
step for single-cell ATAC-seqSo you're only going to be getting reads

1056
01:01:19.220 --> 01:01:23.129
specifically at open regions of chromatin, which we don't really care about

1057
01:01:23.160 --> 01:01:26.500
with methylation. We want to get those regions, but we want to get the regions

1058
01:01:26.540 --> 01:01:27.930
where it's actually repressed.

1059
01:01:28.920 --> 01:01:32.020
So you're almost exclusively going to get hypomethylated regions in these open

1060
01:01:32.040 --> 01:01:35.980
chromatin loci. So we developed a strategy where we take our intact

1061
01:01:36.020 --> 01:01:39.580
nuclei and then actually remove and deplete these

1062
01:01:39.620 --> 01:01:43.050
nucleosomes across the genome to provide genome-wide access for this

1063
01:01:43.240 --> 01:01:46.360
transposase enzyme. So we can get genome-wide coverage.

1064
01:01:46.400 --> 01:01:50.000
So it's essentially ablating that ATAC-seq signal and getting uniform coverage

1065
01:01:50.040 --> 01:01:50.760
across the genome.

1066
01:01:52.660 --> 01:01:56.180
We initially applied this for single-cell whole-genome sequencing, and this is an

1067
01:01:56.220 --> 01:01:59.660
example where we identified some subclones in pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma,

1068
01:02:00.960 --> 01:02:01.080
and

1069
01:02:03.640 --> 01:02:05.460
showed that we could take that strategy.

1070
01:02:05.520 --> 01:02:08.240
But one of the challenges here, and one of the things that we've really wanted to

1071
01:02:08.300 --> 01:02:11.760
move forward with in my lab more and more is making these technologies more

1072
01:02:11.780 --> 01:02:15.320
accessible. No one was doing this technology when we published it, and the reason

1073
01:02:15.360 --> 01:02:16.920
is because you can't get these reagents.

1074
01:02:17.240 --> 01:02:21.160
You had to home brew, custom make a lot of the reagents, which is really a

1075
01:02:21.260 --> 01:02:22.840
barrier for a lot of research programs.

1076
01:02:23.720 --> 01:02:27.240
So not too long ago, we wanted to ameliorate this

1077
01:02:27.380 --> 01:02:30.580
and find a strategy that makes it much more accessible.

1078
01:02:32.100 --> 01:02:35.460
So to that end, we adapted our nucleosome disruption approach and made it so it's

1079
01:02:35.500 --> 01:02:38.940
compatible with the 10x Genomics single-cell ATAC-seq workflow.

1080
01:02:39.520 --> 01:02:43.380
So you can use that off-the-shelf kit with our pretty simple, straightforward

1081
01:02:43.420 --> 01:02:47.260
approach for nucleosome disruption to enable you to get single-cell

1082
01:02:47.300 --> 01:02:49.540
whole-genome sequencing in really high throughput.

1083
01:02:49.760 --> 01:02:52.820
Now, I also want to note this is kind of apples and oranges compared to what

1084
01:02:54.180 --> 01:02:55.420
Nick and Chuck were talking about.

1085
01:02:56.300 --> 01:02:59.160
This is lower coverage. It's not deep coverage.

1086
01:02:59.460 --> 01:03:03.360
You can't really do SNP profiling with this, but you can get copy number profiling.

1087
01:03:04.320 --> 01:03:07.880
And we applied it to this control cell line and then pancreatic

1088
01:03:08.240 --> 01:03:08.910
cancer as well.

1089
01:03:10.840 --> 01:03:12.060
So can we apply this

1090
01:03:12.860 --> 01:03:16.480
nucleosome disruption approach to get genome-wide methylation using our techniques?

1091
01:03:16.500 --> 01:03:18.230
And indeed, we can. The first version of this

1092
01:03:19.280 --> 01:03:23.120
was developed by Ryan Mulqueen, who's now a post-doc in Nick's group.

1093
01:03:23.780 --> 01:03:25.760
This was definitely a proof of principle.

1094
01:03:25.800 --> 01:03:29.760
It was a brutal, I think, 16-hour protocol with no stopping points and

1095
01:03:30.160 --> 01:03:33.249
not super robust, but it was that initial step that showed that it was

1096
01:03:33.260 --> 01:03:36.260
possible. And then we since did a lot of optimizing with

1097
01:03:37.240 --> 01:03:41.120
Ruth in my program to develop a really robust, really high

1098
01:03:41.160 --> 01:03:44.780
coverage, high throughput single-cell DNA methylation

1099
01:03:44.800 --> 01:03:48.520
technology that we're really proud of its really robustness and ability to be able

1100
01:03:48.560 --> 01:03:51.960
to be applied to even tricky tumor samples.

1101
01:03:53.700 --> 01:03:57.260
And then since then, we've scaled this up with our latest version.

1102
01:03:57.720 --> 01:04:00.560
This one has three levels of cell barcoding.

1103
01:04:00.680 --> 01:04:04.240
And as an example Vignet data set, we produced 140,000

1104
01:04:04.700 --> 01:04:05.740
single-cell methylome

1105
01:04:06.800 --> 01:04:08.720
data set in the human cerebral cortex.

1106
01:04:09.130 --> 01:04:13.060
The total library was over 600,000 cells, but we just

1107
01:04:13.100 --> 01:04:14.730
selectively sequenced a subset of it,

1108
01:04:15.820 --> 01:04:17.060
which is kind of a nice aspect of it.

1109
01:04:17.100 --> 01:04:20.680
It works with different conversion methods, and as well

1110
01:04:20.780 --> 01:04:22.880
it's compatible with different sequencing platforms.

1111
01:04:22.920 --> 01:04:25.089
We did a lot of this on Ultima because it was a

1112
01:04:26.140 --> 01:04:29.580
more cost-effective option for us. So most of the data was Ultima.

1113
01:04:29.760 --> 01:04:32.560
And then we have a multi-omic version that I'll touch on a little bit at the end.

1114
01:04:34.340 --> 01:04:38.200
But I do want to make a quick plug for our single-cell methylation analysis tool

1115
01:04:38.240 --> 01:04:38.980
called AMETHYST.

1116
01:04:40.800 --> 01:04:43.470
One of the things-- and this is developed by Lauren Rouleau, who's staying in my

1117
01:04:43.540 --> 01:04:47.309
lab. There's a GitHub with lots of tutorials, and the goal of

1118
01:04:47.360 --> 01:04:51.060
this was really to make it a kind of one-stop shop for single-cell DNA methylation

1119
01:04:51.120 --> 01:04:51.660
analysis.

1120
01:04:52.460 --> 01:04:53.640
Our goal here was to

1121
01:04:54.560 --> 01:04:58.080
get the analysis tools in the hands of the biologist that's doing the data.

1122
01:04:59.240 --> 01:05:03.040
So to that end, we really put a lot of work into the visualization tools so

1123
01:05:03.100 --> 01:05:07.000
that biologists can get their raw data, take it through this workflow, and start to

1124
01:05:07.040 --> 01:05:10.660
look at the genes of interest and understand the biology of the methylomes.

1125
01:05:11.360 --> 01:05:12.440
I like these plots in the middle here.

1126
01:05:12.480 --> 01:05:15.809
There's PBMCs on the left where the rows are the different cell types, and then

1127
01:05:15.880 --> 01:05:19.050
brain on the right. And the blue are these hypomethylated regions.

1128
01:05:19.420 --> 01:05:23.220
And you can see there's high cell type specificity, and these black boxes are

1129
01:05:23.260 --> 01:05:25.200
the differentially methylated regions that were called.

1130
01:05:26.000 --> 01:05:28.880
So it's a really nice way to visualize and interact with the data.

1131
01:05:29.160 --> 01:05:32.500
And I think it's really important to be able to develop those tools to really allow

1132
01:05:32.520 --> 01:05:35.780
the biologists to really be digging into the data.

1133
01:05:36.840 --> 01:05:39.610
Using AMETHYST and SKI-MAPv3,

1134
01:05:41.120 --> 01:05:43.540
I'm going to touch on a vignette here.

1135
01:05:43.660 --> 01:05:47.220
And I mentioned non-CG methylation is not present in most cell types.

1136
01:05:47.520 --> 01:05:51.500
That's true, except in neurons. So I know this is a cancer meeting, but

1137
01:05:51.520 --> 01:05:54.280
this is a cool vignette where

1138
01:05:56.120 --> 01:05:59.820
seminal work by Joe Ecker showed that when you're born, your neurons, you actually

1139
01:05:59.830 --> 01:06:03.800
don't have any of this non-CG methylation, but through the first several years

1140
01:06:03.840 --> 01:06:06.920
of life up to adolescence, it actually accumulates in your neurons.

1141
01:06:06.940 --> 01:06:10.720
So it's this postnatal maturation of your neurons during

1142
01:06:10.780 --> 01:06:12.560
this peak window of synaptogenesis.

1143
01:06:14.200 --> 01:06:15.460
And we really wanted to study this.

1144
01:06:15.520 --> 01:06:18.740
So in mice, this corresponds to P7 to P28.

1145
01:06:18.900 --> 01:06:22.460
So we took these regions in the mouse brain, five microdissected regions, sorted

1146
01:06:22.500 --> 01:06:25.440
for neurons and profiled them using our SKI-MAPv3

1147
01:06:25.460 --> 01:06:29.300
technology. And we were able to produce this really comprehensive

1148
01:06:29.340 --> 01:06:32.000
atlas of postnatal neuronal maturation.

1149
01:06:32.340 --> 01:06:35.770
So this is about 240,000 high-coverage single-cell methylomes,

1150
01:06:36.520 --> 01:06:40.320
where we're able to show all of these branching lineages of early

1151
01:06:40.540 --> 01:06:44.280
neurons and then differentiating out into these very specific

1152
01:06:44.300 --> 01:06:45.120
neuronal subtypes.

1153
01:06:46.520 --> 01:06:50.080
And just a vignette that I think highlights how you can use this single-cell

1154
01:06:50.140 --> 01:06:53.920
methylation data that's applicable across all sorts of tissue types and

1155
01:06:54.120 --> 01:06:57.360
certainly cancer, where there's a lot of evolution in cell state dynamics.

1156
01:06:58.800 --> 01:07:02.650
As an example of looking at the pseudo temporal ordering of the progression of

1157
01:07:02.720 --> 01:07:06.020
methylomes in this branch from MGE-derived

1158
01:07:06.340 --> 01:07:08.140
GABAergic neurons. So these are inhibitory neurons

1159
01:07:08.960 --> 01:07:11.360
branching either into parvalbumin or somatostatin.

1160
01:07:11.980 --> 01:07:15.720
And you can see here's a couple genes here where in the

1161
01:07:15.760 --> 01:07:19.620
parvalbumin branch, we're getting dramatic increase in methylation as we go through

1162
01:07:19.640 --> 01:07:22.812
pseudoage.With a lot less in somatostatin.

1163
01:07:23.272 --> 01:07:26.932
And conversely, here at this gene, we get a clear

1164
01:07:26.992 --> 01:07:30.752
hypomethylated window that is not the case in progressive increasing in

1165
01:07:30.772 --> 01:07:34.272
methylation in the other branch. So you get clear branch-specific

1166
01:07:34.872 --> 01:07:38.652
methylation patterns. And these concepts can be applied across any dynamic

1167
01:07:38.712 --> 01:07:39.112
system.

1168
01:07:40.732 --> 01:07:43.942
And we have lots of other kind of really novel, exciting discoveries in this that

1169
01:07:43.972 --> 01:07:47.332
really get into the neuroscience, but I'll leave that for those of you that are

1170
01:07:47.392 --> 01:07:50.452
interested in neuroscience and can look up the preprint, which will be coming out

1171
01:07:50.512 --> 01:07:52.752
hopefully in the next few weeks or so.

1172
01:07:54.592 --> 01:07:57.691
So finally, I wanted to touch on how we've taken this to the multi-omics space.

1173
01:07:59.912 --> 01:08:00.722
So we have our

